<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.D. Leafy Spurge Problem Growing / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Leafy spurge continues to grow in North  
Dakota despite a state program to distribute weed-eating bugs to 
whomever wants them. 
</P>
<P>
	North Dakota acreage affected by leafy spurge acres increased  
from about 932,000 in 1991 to 1.1 million last year, said John 
Leppert, noxious weeds specialist with the state Agriculture 
Department. The weed, if left unchecked, crowds out prairie grass, 
rendering pastures useless. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, it's getting worse,'' Leppert said. ``Anybody driving  
around North Dakota would have to be blind not to see that spurge 
is all over the place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leppert said the problem would be much worse if not for the flea  
beetle program. The beetles feed on the spurge plant, and their 
larvae tunnel through the weed's roots. Since 1991, they've been 
given to landowners free of charge during annual summer 
distribution campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's campaign got under way last week in a Burleigh  
County field, where landowners came to sweep nets over leafy spurge 
plants and collect flea beetles to introduce in other pastures. 
</P>
<P>
	Russ Arman, who owns pasture land in Grant County, collected  
bugs for the seventh consecutive year. He said the beetles are 
helping to control the spurge on his land, but he's frustrated that 
many ranchers in the county don't take the weed problem very 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see where your efforts make a difference, but you might  
have a neighbor not doing anything,'' Arman said. ``And if you're 
downriver of them, you get a new spurge crop every spring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The weed spreads through seeds and an extensive root system.  
</P>
<P>
	Leppert said there are many landowners who recognize the  
seriousness of the problem and are taking steps to address it. 
</P>
<P>
	However, ``a lot of people aren't interested, or they think it's  
somebody else's problem,'' he said. ``We need to get more people 
involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Dunn, who raises alfalfa for his horses on six acres south  
of Bismarck, said he decided to get involved this year after 
watching the leafy spurge problem on his land worsen every year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hard to find four, five years ago, but every year I can  
tell that it's increased its range,'' he said. ``This beetle 
business, if it works, will be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-two million flea beetles were distributed to landowners  
last summer. Officials hope to increase that number this year 
during distribution events in 15 counties, Johnson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
