<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About Detroit Auto Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. AUTO CONTRACT TALKS   	
</P>
<P>
	Companies: General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., DaimlerChrysler  
AG. 
</P>
<P>
	Union: United Auto Workers, Detroit.  
</P>
<P>
	Current contract: Signed in 1996, expires Sept. 14.  
</P>
<P>
	Workers affected: About 407,000 total; 222,000 at GM, 110,000 at  
Ford, 75,000 at DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	Significance: Though their influence is less significant today,  
the Detroit contracts historically have set precedents for wages, 
workplace improvements and benefits that later became standards 
throughout U.S. industry. UAW members remain among the highest-paid 
blue-collar workers in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Process: Introductory ``handshake ceremonies'' this week  
followed by initial presentations by company and union leaders. 
Bargaining committees then break into subcommittees to address 
union demands through August. Union typically picks a ``lead 
company'' by Labor Day, based on which has the best proposal on the 
table. Talks then intensify to reach an economic agreement with 
that company, which the other companies are expected to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	UAW chief negotiators: Richard Shoemaker, GM; Ron Gettelfinger,  
Ford; Jack Laskowski, DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	Management chief negotiators: Gary Cowger, GM; Robert Marcin,  
Ford; Thomas Gallagher, DaimlerChrysler. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
