<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 14:35:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aid Workers Follow Troops to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Aid workers armed with enough flour  
to bake 45,000 loaves of bread and thousands of ready-to-eat meals 
rolled into Kosovo on Sunday, following rifle-toting soldiers in 
the second stage of the region's peace plan. 
</P>
<P>
	While the NATO force is to rebuild law and order in Kosovo, the  
aid workers are to help reconstruct civilian life. Eventually, that 
will mean restoring a court system, municipal administrations, even 
holding elections. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``first and foremost is the humanitarian task,'' said Sergio  
Vieira de Mello, the U.N. interim special representative for 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieira de Mello led fewer than 100 U.N. and other aid workers  
into Kosovo from neighboring Macedonia on Sunday, taking the same 
route NATO tanks rumbled over at the start of the peacekeeping 
deployment Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The humanitarian convoy included 50 trucks loaded with food,  
blankets, bottled water, tents and plastic sheeting that will be 
distributed over the next few days. 
</P>
<P>
	World Food Program spokeswoman Christiane Berthiaume said the  
aid brought in Sunday included 48,000 ready-to-eat meals donated by 
the United States. The meals, similar to those soldiers are issued, 
included crackers, beans, lentils, jam and cookies. 
</P>
<P>
	The flour was to distributed to Kosovo bakeries. The initial aid  
team's first priority was assessment -- which bakeries could handle 
how much of the huge load, which roads and bridges could handle the 
weight of loaded aid trucks, which warehouses could store food. One 
of two U.N. warehouses in Kosovo was discovered Sunday to have been 
burned. 
</P>
<P>
	The initial aid is for an estimated 500,000-600,000 people  
believed to be displaced within Kosovo. Another 860,000 who fled to 
neighboring countries were being advised to stay in camps, with the 
situation in Kosovo still being too insecure and uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the refugees start coming back in large numbers, that would  
be a huge problem,'' Berthiaume said. 
</P>
<P>
	Vieira de Mello said he was confident the peacekeeping and  
humanitarian missions would one day make Kosovo safe for both the 
ethnic Albanian refugees who have been fleeing for months and the 
Serbs who have been leaving since the peace plan was signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Serbs fear retribution for the part some of them played in the  
campaign to drive Albanians from Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
