<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pres. Bush To Stay Out of Son's Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) -- With a promise to ``stay out of his  
way,'' former President George Bush said Sunday that his son is 
prepared to follow his footsteps to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``My contribution will be letting him find his own way,'' the  
former president said in a picture-taking session promoting George 
W. Bush's 2000 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush men were joined by their wives: Barbara Bush and  
daughter-in-law Laura. Rounding a corner at her family's summer 
estate and spying 150 journalists, the former first lady quipped, 
``Where were you in `92?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The reminder of her husband's failed 1992 reelection campaign  
broke the ice. It was all smiles and giggles and warm hellos after 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like old times,'' the ex-president said as he walked  
up to a microphone set in front of a breathtaking view of the 
Atlantic Ocean. He nodded and waved to familiar faces in the press 
corps. 
</P>
<P>
	His son, the twice-elected Texas governor and front-running GOP  
presidential candidate, kidded the father for jumping out of an 
airplane last week to celebrate his 75th birthday. ``Happy 
birthday, Sky King,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And his mother made her endorsement official. ``I think we did  
right with this boy,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bush visited his parents between campaigns stops in  
Iowa and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Family Bush is an American political dynasty. The former  
president's father, Prescott Bush, was a U.S. senator. Two of his 
sons -- Jeb of Florida and George W. of Texas -- are Republican 
governors. 
</P>
<P>
	A few feet from the Bushes, a Texas flag whipped in the wind  
beneath the Stars and Stripes. When Jeb visits, the Florida flag 
also waves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like dynasty-type stuff,'' said the former president,  
wearing a blue jacket from the Camp David presidential retreat. 
``We never felt we were entitled to anything, and dynasty connotes 
a kind of expectation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Texas governor clearly hopes to benefit from the family  
name. He is raising money and drawing talent from his father's 
political network. 
</P>
<P>
	A new Time magazine survey suggested 63 percent of Americans see  
George W. Bush as a lot like his father. A Newsweek poll found 49 
percent of respondents felt being the son of a former president 
will help him. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Bush's popularity has risen since he left office,  
although some social conservatives who dominate early primary 
voting still resent him for breaking his no-new-taxes pledge. 
</P>
<P>
	George W. will set his own course, father and son agree.  
</P>
<P>
	``I will stay out of the issue business in terms of the  
campaign,'' the former president said. ``I think that's the right 
way to do it. I had my chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he might help raise money if asked by his son.  
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't need a voice from the past,'' the elder Bush said.  
``I'll try to stay out of his way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bush says he learned a lot from his father's defeat,  
including that ``I'll still have a great life'' if he loses. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Bush was an ambassador to China, head of the GOP,  
director of the CIA and vice president before becoming president -- 
a resume much longer than his son's. But he said his son has 
``executive experience'' and will probably be a better campaigner. 
</P>
<P>
	When the session ended, Bush the son held out his right hand --  
palm up. Bush the father clapped his hand into his son's. There was 
a loud smack, and they shook. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 21:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O's Ripken Has First Six-Hit Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Orioles' Cal Ripken had the first six-hit  
game of his career -- the first ever by a Baltimore player -- against 
the Braves on Sunday night, including two homers that moved him 
past Johnny Bench and Graig Nettles into 32nd place on the career 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was 6-for-6 with six RBIs, raising his average to .331.  
He hadn't gotten five hits in a game since May 5, 1985 at 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of nice at 38 to have a first in your career,''  
Ripken said. ``Everything has to go right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since coming off the disabled list in mid-May, Ripken is hitting  
.367 (40-for-109), raising his season average to .328. Sunday 
night's performance lifted his batting average by 30 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was seeing the ball pretty well. I got some good pitches to  
drive,'' he said. ``I had a good swing and the ball fell. It's the 
kind of night you hope to duplicate, but you probably won't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His first homer, a three-run shot, capped a five-run opening  
inning for the Orioles. He added a two-run homer in the fourth to 
stretch Baltimore's lead to 11-0, drawing a standing, towel-waving 
ovation from the Atlanta fans as he crossed home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles third baseman, best-known for his record playing  
streak, now has 391 homers in his career, breaking from tie with 
Johnny Bench (389) and moving past Nettles (390) as well. Next on 
the list: Joe Carter with 396. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken has 17 two-homer games in his career, the last coming at  
Detroit on Sept. 15, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the homers and a run-scoring double in the  
seventh, Ripken also had singles in the third, sixth and ninth 
innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
