<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton, Yeltsin To Talk  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton and Russian President Boris  
Yeltsin are expected to speak by telephone today to discuss 
Russia's role in the Kosovo peacekeeping force. Meanwhile, U.S. 
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met with Foreign Minister 
Igor Ivanov, following up drawn-out talks over the previous 48 
hours. He said the U.S. was considering ``a zone of 
responsibility'' for Russian peacekeepers, the Interfax news agency 
reported. He did not elaborate, and it was unclear whether NATO 
would bend on Russian demands over a separate sector outside NATO 
control. 

</P>
<P>
	Russians Not Budging From Airport  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A small group of Russian soldiers  
remained largely in control of a vital airport in Kosovo's capital 
today. NATO convoys appear to be barred from entering most of the 
airport area, although allied troops fanned out around the rest of 
Kosovo's capital and British forces rode through downtown. NATO and 
Russian commanders met face-to-face yesterday to discuss control of 
the airport, but results were inconclusive. But Britain's SKY news 
reported that NATO and Russian commanders had reached a deal on 
sharing the runway. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Says He Will Win Nomination  
</P>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- George W. Bush, the untested  
presidential front-runner, plunged into the 2000 campaign today by 
dropping any pretense that he is only considering a campaign. ``You 
can expect someone named George W. to win this nomination,'' the 
Texas governor said. Addressing supporters on his first campaign 
trip, Bush left no doubt that his ``exploratory committee'' will 
evolve into a full-fledged campaign. ``I'm ready,'' he told about 
200 supporters who greeted him at the airport. ``I intend to win 
this nomination the old-fashioned way and that is to earn it.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Deadly Virus Said To Be Stockpiled  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Government officials reportedly believe Russia,  
Iraq and North Korea are stockpiling the deadly smallpox virus for 
military use. The New York Times reported Sunday a secret federal 
intelligence assessment was completed late last year. The paper 
says it was based on evidence from a senior Soviet defector and 
blood samples from North Korean soldiers showing smallpox 
vaccinations. Officials told the Times the assessment was an 
important factor in President Clinton's recent decision to not 
destroy American stockpiles of the virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Small Cruise Ship Runs Aground  
</P>
<P>
	JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) -- Fifty six passengers and 24 crew members  
were evacuated yesterday when a small cruise ship ran aground. No 
injuries were reported. The 157-foot Wilderness Adventurer struck 
rocks and grounded in Dundas Bay, about 50 miles west of Juneau, 
the Coast Guard said. Absorbent booms were deployed around the ship 
to try to contain any spilled fuel. The ship is owned and operated 
by Glacier Bay Tours of Juneau. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Pays Speeding Ticket in Pennies  
</P>
<P>
	CLAUDE, Texas (AP) -- Angry about a $135 speeding ticket, an  
Amarillo man decided to give the authorities a penny for their 
thoughts -- actually, 13,513 pennies. Randy McCain paid an extra $40 
to have 270 rolls of pennies delivered to an Armstrong County 
Justice of the Peace on Thursday. The coins weighed in at 78 
pounds. ``The bank in Claude was mad,'' the judge told the Amarillo 
Globe-News. ``I thought it was hilarious.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Baltimore Blanks Atlanta 5-0  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- After suffering through a disappointing season,  
the Baltimore Orioles last night beat the Atlanta Braves 5-0. Juan 
Guzman pitched a six-hitter, drove in a run with his first 
major-league hit and got plenty of support when Brady Anderson, 
Mike Bordick and Will Clark homered in the first inning. Albert 
Belle, who was benched Friday night after a shouting match with 
manager Ray Miller, returned to right field and the cleanup spot in 
the batting order. He went 2-for-4 with a stolen base and an 
intentional walk. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Take Game 3 From Sabres  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Joe Nieuwendyk, almost forced to score with  
Brett Hull out and Mike Modano hampered by a serious wrist injury, 
had two goals and the depleted Stars regained home-ice advantage in 
the Stanley Cup finals by beating the Buffalo Sabres 2-1 Saturday 
night. The Stars take a 2-1 edge into Game 4 on Tuesday, with two 
of the final three games, if necessary, in Dallas. Dallas had every 
reason to lose but didn't, killing off eight Buffalo power plays -- 
one a two-man advantage -- and overcoming a groin injury that forced 
Hull to the locker room after less than three minutes of ice time. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
