<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 20:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tropical Storm Builds in Atlantic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Tropical Storm Arlene, the first of the season, saw  
its top winds drop from 60 mph to 50 mph late Sunday and was still 
spinning almost aimlessly deep in the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm posed no immediate threat to land.  
</P>
<P>
	Forecasters said it still could gather some strength Monday, and  
the storm might threaten Bermuda at some point beyond the reach of 
the National Hurricane Center's three-day forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the (U.S.) East Coast is in the future of this  
storm, but Bermuda -- we'll be looking at that. But it's not a big 
deal right now,'' said hurricane specialist Miles Lawrence. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 p.m. EDT, Arlene's center was near 29.3 north latitude and  
59.6 west longitude, or about 375 miles east-southeast of Bermuda 
and 1,250 miles from the Florida coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Storm-force winds of 39 mph extended up to 105 miles from the  
center, which was heading west at near 5 mph. Arlene was expected 
to make a gradual turn toward the northwest either Monday or 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
