<DOCNO> APW19990613.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 06:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Runner Marion Jones Returns to N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Marion Jones won the long jump on her sixth  
leap after three scratches Saturday at the Pontiac Grand Prix 
Invitational, an effort that was the best by an American this year 
but left her lying in the sand pit gripping her knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones went 23 feet on her final jump to overtake Adrien Sawyer,  
who jumped 22-4 1/2, and hyperextended her knee in the process. Sawyer 
had the best American jump this year, 22-5 1/4. Jones was one-half 
inch short of the best jump in the world this year by Fiona May of 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-event meet was held at the North Carolina State track  
where Jones trains six times a week. It was the final competition 
for most U.S. athletes before the USA Championships later this 
month in Eugene, Ore. The meet was held before the Foot Locker 
Outdoor Championships for high school athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones zipped down the runway on her first two jumps, but  
couldn't best 22-1 3/4 on either attempt. She encouraged the crowd to 
cheer her on by clapping her hands over her head, but on the next 
three jumps she scratched. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the first legal jump, it was time to crank it up,''  
Jones said. ``I definitely had a seven-meter jump in me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After landing on her sixth and final try, Jones grabbed her  
right knee and sat in the pit until her distance was measured. 
Jones was able to walk away and later came to the awards platform 
with an ice pack wrapped around her knee. She described the injury 
as a hyperextension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I came down wrong on my knee,'' Jones said. ``I think I scared  
myself a little bit. ... Sitting here now, I'm not really concerned 
about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After she won, Jones was surrounded by high school athletes  
snapping pictures and clamoring for autographs as she iced her 
right knee. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's my hero,'' said 15-year-old Chinel Davis, a sprinter and  
long jumper from Bardonia, N.Y. Jodi Schlesinger, 18, a triple 
jumper from Bardonia, said she was going to take some of the sand 
from the long jump pit as a souvenir. 
</P>
<P>
	Jearl Miles-Clark was clocked in 50.68 seconds in the 400  
meters, the best time in the world this year. The best clocking had 
been 50.76 by Cathy Freeman of Australia and Suziann Reid of the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Regina Jacobs improved her best time of this year in the 800 --  
1:59.64 -- with a 1:58.55. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was so inspired by all the high school athletes, I was not  
going to dog it around the track,'' said Jacobs, who admits she's a 
high school track ``junkie.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 06:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
