<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vaccine-Refusing Marines Face Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TWENTYNINE PALMS, Calif. (AP) -- A military judge ruled on Friday  
that five Marines who refused to take anthrax vaccinations must 
face separate courts-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Ken Martin also sharply limited the evidence that the  
defense may use at the trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he was ``not going to second-guess the secretary of  
defense,'' Martin denied a defense request to call more than three 
dozen witnesses to testify about the vaccine's safety and 
effectiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	The five have pleaded innocent to charges of refusing to obey an  
order. If convicted, they face up to six months in jail, bad 
conduct discharges, fines and reduction to the rank of private. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants are among about 200 U.S. military personnel who  
have refused Pentagon-ordered vaccinations intended to protect them 
in case anthrax is used in biological warfare. They have raised 
questions about possible side effects, including sterility. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense had said it wanted to put the vaccine on trial.  
</P>
<P>
	``While this was not entirely unexpected, the judge has severely  
limited the scope of what we will be able to argue,'' said Mark 
Zaid, a civilian attorney for the men. ``We won't be able to call 
in people to challenge its safety, which is what we wanted to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Facing trial are Jason Austin, 22, of Fritch, Texas; Michael  
McIntyre, 22, of Mount Vernon, Wash.; Jared Johnston, 19, of 
Henryetta, Okla.; Michael Metzig, 20, of San Diego; and Jared 
Schwartz, 20, Henderson, Ky. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:26:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qwest Bids $55B for Telecom Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Qwest Communications International Inc. made a  
surprising $55 billion offer Sunday to acquire U S West Inc. and 
Frontier Corp. in a bold move to bust their agreement to merge with 
Global Crossing Inc. and create a telecommunications powerhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver-based Qwest is the nation's fourth-largest long-distance  
telephone company. The deal would give Qwest a piece of the local 
phone markets in 14 western states with the addition of Baby Bell U 
S West and strengthen Qwest's long distance business with the 
addition of Frontier, the No. 5 long-distance company. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest is offering $78 a share in stock for U S West and $73 a  
share in cash and stock for Frontier. Qwest would sweeten each bid 
by $2 a share if both companies agree to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Both those bids are higher than Global Crossing's offer to pay  
about $63 a share in stock for both U S West and Frontier in 
separate deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing is a Bermuda-based startup company with plans to  
link the world's continents with high-speed Internet cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing stock, however, has fallen 16 percent in recent  
weeks as the companies have had a hard time selling investors on 
the benefits of combining their businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the clear superiority of our offer to the proposed  
Global Crossing merger, we would like to meet with you and your 
advisors as soon as possible,'' wrote Joseph P. Nacchio, Qwest 
chariman and chief executive officer, in letters to the heads of U 
S West and Frontier. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing officials declined comment on the deal Sunday. U  
S West and Frontier officials could not immediately be reached. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet is revolutionizing the telecommunications industry  
and is driving a string of merger bids. As high-speed connections 
link more homes and businesses, telecom and cable companies alike 
are betting big on the potential profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AT&AMP;T Corp. won a bidding war with Comcast for  
MediaOne Group Inc., a Denver-based cable company. AT&AMP;T, the 
nation's largest long distance company, is gambling that television 
cables will be the way to carry Internet, voice and data traffic in 
the future. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 15:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caps' Owners Have Some New Ideas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Watch the guy selling hot dogs at the MCI  
Center next season. He just might be the owner. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, the Washington Capitals were in the Stanley Cup  
finals. This season, they were out of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the team has new owners who are intent on reviving the  
Capitals, on the ice and at the gate. Ted Leonsis and Jonathan 
Ledecky are promising the same kind of innovative ideas that made 
them millionaires in computers and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be very accessible,'' Ledecky said. ``We're  
going to be at all the games, and we're going to wear beepers so 
there if fans are having problems with their game experience they 
can dial a number and get us. 
</P>
<P>
	``I personally plan to take on all the different functions at  
the arena and literally be a concession stand guy and a guy selling 
hot dogs and sodas in the crowd and sitting with the fans in the 
upper deck. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have buttons that say, `Hi, I'm the owner, ask  
me a question. It's going to be wild, wild in a positive way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Capitals, who lost about $20 million last season, have a  
season-ticket base of 4,000-5,000 fans. These days, it takes a 
minimum of 12,000 season tickets just to get an expansion 
franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	High ticket prices, a losing season after last year's success  
and the lack of hockey tradition make the team a hard sell. It's 
not unusual to hear fans of the visiting team outcheer the home 
fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you how rock bottom it is,'' Leonsis said. ``Two  
weeks ago I went to the local book store, and they must have 
100,000 books there. I went to the sports section and there were 
racks and racks, literally 100 books on baseball, basketball, 10 
books on Michael Jordan alone, 20 books on golf, 20 books on 
bodybuilding, 10 books on mountain climbing -- and there were three 
books on hockey. So when I asked the woman at the checkout counter 
why, she said, `No one here loves hockey.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis, 42, is the president of the interactive properties  
group with America Online. Ledecky, 41, is the founder, cofounder 
or director of 10 publicly traded companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Along with team president Dick Patrick, they bought the Capitals  
from 75-year-old Abe Pollin for about $80 million, ushering in a 
new generation of ideas based on old-fashioned concepts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe this sounds corny, but I think the players should meet  
and thank the fans all the time,'' Leonsis said. ``I think the 
players should shake hands before games, and I think the players 
should be in chat rooms. I think the players should be posting 
their own message boards. I think the players should be scheduling 
events online so the fans can get to know them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If history is any indication, Leonsis will accomplish his goals.  
</P>
<P>
	In 1987, Leonsis was on a flight from Miami to Atlanta when the  
plane lost its flaps and landing gear. The passengers had about a 
half-hour to consider their fates before the pilot attempted, 
successfully, a very rough landing. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a long time,'' Leonsis said. ``I was nervous, frankly.  
I didn't want to die. I just said if I live, I'm going to play 
offense for the rest of my life. 
</P>
<P>
	``About a week later, over the weekend, I wrote down 101 things  
to do before I die, and I try to do two or three a year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first 25 were sports-related -- Leonsis was single at the  
time -- and the goals included playing Augusta National golf course, 
catching a foul ball, making a hole in one, meeting Mickey Mantle, 
buying a sports team, winning an NBA championship and winning a 
Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The nonsports items included meeting the president, publishing a  
novel, making a movie, doing a standup comedy routine and traveling 
to outer space. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that he's bought the Capitals, Leonsis says he's  
accomplished ``68 or 69'' of the 101. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been clipping them off,'' he said. ``So it really has  
been a way to coalesce my thinking, goals I want to achieve. So 
when this opportunity came up, I jumped at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leonsis envisions a five-year turnaround for the Capitals from a  
marketing standpoint. The first step will probably be a reduction 
in ticket prices, followed by an upgrade in the entertainment 
offered during timeouts and intermissions. He and Ledecky watched 
many recent playoff games, including Boston vs. Buffalo, taking 
notes along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll know we've arrived when it's like Boston, where there was  
like two dozen fans from Buffalo,'' Leonsis said. ``And whenever 
they stood up to cheer, they were just cheered over. You didn't 
know they existed. That would be a good barometer of when we've 
arrived.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 06:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Victory Gallop Wins Stephen Foster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer Elliott Walden wasn't sure how  
Victory Gallop would fare in his first start since a third-place 
finish in the Dubai World Cup in March. 
</P>
<P>
	His questions were answered quickly Saturday as the 4-year-old  
winner of the 1998 Belmont Stakes ran 1 1/8 miles in a track-record 
1:47.28 to win the $827,250 Stephen Foster Handicap for 3-year-olds 
and up at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This horse has been training just great,'' Walden said. ``I  
must have had 10 people come up to me the last two days and tell me 
I was a cinch just from seeing him train. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know about that Dubai thing. I've been waiting to  
run him and had been excited about it. Everybody wants to label the 
fact that they don't come back from Dubai well. I hope this puts it 
to bed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The advertised showdown between two former Triple Crown race  
winners eventually turned into a one-horse show. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Jerry Bailey and carrying 120 pounds, Victory Gallop --  
who finished second in the 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness to 
Real Quiet -- breezed past 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner 
Silver Charm in the stretch and beat him by 8 1/2 lengths. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-year-old gray, ridden by 1999 Kentucky Derby and Preakness  
winner Chris Antley and carrying a race-high 123 pounds, broke 
strong but flattened out in the final furlong in losing his fourth 
consecutive race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just kind of ran an even race,'' said Antley, who was  
aboard the Bob Baffert-trained colt for the first time. ``I thought 
I had him in pretty good position but he just didn't fire when we 
needed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Victory Gallop, who earned $512,895, went off at 6-5 and paid  
$4.60, $2.60 and $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Nite Dreamer, who carried 110 pounds and was ridden by Pat Day,  
finished second, five lengths back, and paid $4.80 and $2.10. 
Littlebitlively, who carried 115 pounds and was ridden by Calvin 
Borel, was another three-quarters of a length back in third and 
paid $2.10. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Silver Charm were Precocity, Da Devil and Connecting  
Terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Littlebitlively, who lost by a head to Silver Charm in last  
year's Clark Handicap, dueled with Connecting Terms for the first 
three-quarters of a mile. As the field moved around the far turn, 
Nite Dreamer made his bid for the lead as Victory Gallop charged 
from the back of the seven-horse field to take the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey said he was amazed by the power in Victory Gallop's  
stride as he took the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``He dropped back farther than I thought he would, about 12 or  
14 lengths off the lead,'' Bailey said. ``He was content to be 
there until I pulled the trigger. And then it was the most powerful 
rush I've felt around a turn since I've been riding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cigar made strong moves all the way in races, but when horses  
take off like that and make up the kind of time he did today, it's 
just devastating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ride was Antley's first major race since pulling up an  
injured Charismatic as the colt neared the finish line in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic broke two bones in his lower left foot and was  
retired following surgery to repair the damage. Veterinarians 
credited Antley, who jumped off and immediately picked the leg up 
to keep weight off it, with preventing more serious damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I truly feel revived because the horse is OK -- that was my  
biggest concern,'' Antley said. ``Charismatic has given me so much 
in my career and my comeback. ... He gave me some of my greatest 
moments ever. I felt something was wrong and what I did was simply 
instinct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Antley said Charismatic had been on his mind a lot since the  
Belmont but had no effect on the way he rode Silver Charm on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``New race, new horse, new beginning and a lot of hope,'' Antley  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 06:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Victory Gallop Wins Stephen Foster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer Elliott Walden wasn't sure how  
Victory Gallop would fare in his first start since a third-place 
finish in the Dubai World Cup in March. 
</P>
<P>
	His questions were answered quickly Saturday as the 4-year-old  
winner of the 1998 Belmont Stakes ran 1 1/8 miles in a track-record 
1:47.28 to win the $827,250 Stephen Foster Handicap for 3-year-olds 
and up at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This horse has been training just great,'' Walden said. ``I  
must have had 10 people come up to me the last two days and tell me 
I was a cinch just from seeing him train. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know about that Dubai thing. I've been waiting to  
run him and had been excited about it. Everybody wants to label the 
fact that they don't come back from Dubai well. I hope this puts it 
to bed.'' 
