<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 18:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drunk Driving Penalties Tougher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reflecting tougher punishment for those who  
mix drinking and driving, more than half a million motorists were 
on probation or behind bars for DWI in 1997, almost twice the level 
of the mid-1980s, the government said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	During the same period, drunken driving arrests dropped -- from  
1.8 million in 1986 to 1.5 million in 1997 -- even though the number 
of licensed drivers increased almost 15 percent, to 183 million, 
the Justice Department's Bureau of Justice Statistics announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The bureau attributed the decline in arrests in part to the  
aging of licensed drivers. Younger drivers are more prone to drink 
and drive. In 1997, 54 percent of licensed drivers were aged 40 or 
older, up from 46 percent in 1986. The older the driver over age 
21, the lower the rate of DWI arrests, the government reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Of those convicted of DWI in 1997, 454,500 were on probation,  
41,100 were in local jails and 17,600 were in state prisons. In 
1986, 270,000 people were behind bars or on probation for DWI. 
</P>
<P>
	One expert said the figures reflect success in getting ``social  
drinkers'' to become more responsible and failure in dealing with 
the hardest-core group of drunken drivers: those who have a serious 
problem with alcohol. 
</P>
<P>
	Without alcohol treatment programs, ``these are just drunk  
drivers waiting to get back on the road,'' said Terry Schiavone, 
president of the National Commission Against Drunk Driving, a 
private group. ``Jail and probation have never cured the drunken 
driving problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-six percent of DWI offenders on probation were in alcohol  
treatment programs in 1997, according to the bureau study. 
</P>
<P>
	Support for Schiavone's view that the half million drivers now  
under correctional supervision are ``hard-core'' includes: 
</P>
<P>
	--About half of DWI offenders in local jails reported consuming  
the equivalent of about 12 beers or six glasses of wine in the 
hours leading up to their arrest. About half those on probation 
said they had been drinking for at least three hours before their 
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	--A third of DWI offenders on probation said they drank every day  
and two-thirds of them said they had used drugs in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	--A third of DWI offenders on probation and nearly two-thirds of  
those incarcerated reported prior DWI sentences. Eight percent of 
those on probation reported three or more previous DWI offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	For every 1,000 DWI arrests in 1997, 347 offenders were jailed  
or placed on probation -- up from 151 in 1986, according to the 
study. The punishment rate continues a trend that began in the late 
1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	In its survey based on interviews with the offenders and  
record-gathering, the Justice Department concluded: 
</P>
<P>
	--People convicted of DWI are about five years older, better  
educated and more often white than those convicted of other crimes. 
Men account for over 90 percent of DWI offenders in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	--In 1990, 327 of every 1,000 people arrested for DWI were on  
probation or behind bars, more than double the figure of 151 just 
four years earlier. In 1990, the number of drivers under 
correctional supervision was actually greater than it was seven 
years later, 593,000 compared to 513,200 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	--Convicted DWI offenders in jail were sentenced to serve 11  
months on average, while state prisoners convicted of DWI were 
sentenced to serve an average of 49 months. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 13:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Volleyball Player Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jeni Jones sat on the bed and held her  
arms straight out. They felt like jelly. 
</P>
<P>
	With one hand the doctor pushed down lightly on an arm. It  
easily gave way, bouncing off her hip and dangling in front of her. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks earlier, the 5-foot-10 middle blocker with 9-foot-8  
vertical reach had been one of the best athletes at the University 
of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Now she was stricken with a rare virus that rendered her muscles  
nearly useless. She was expected to miss a year. Maybe her career 
was through. 
</P>
<P>
	Her finely tuned body had been ravaged by Guillain-Barre  
syndrome, which causes temporary paralysis and leaves some victims 
incapacitated for years. Her determination, however, never 
slackened. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine months after the humbling encounter in the hospital, Jones  
was again one of Florida's best athletes. She returned for her 
senior season stronger than before. 
</P>
<P>
	Her comeback earned her the Honda Inspiration Award, given  
annually to a female athlete who has overcome physical adversity. 
It will be presented Monday in Reno, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anybody who was around Jeni during that time  
could walk away without being affected,'' Florida coach Mary Wise 
said. ``Watching the onset of the illness and then watching how 
hard she worked to come back, you had to be affected by it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' mother, Ann Bunn, drove from Birmingham, Ala., and kept  
vigil in the hospital, watching her daughter deteriorate during 
nine fretful days. Later, in Alabama, Bunn heard the daily reports 
as the team, Jones' friends and coaches helped her on the road 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think 99 percent of the people would have dropped out of  
school, come home, rested, taken an incomplete, come back the next 
year,'' Bunn said. ``Jeni wasn't about to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The virus struck quickly. It was Halloween night in Columbia,  
S.C., hours before an important match against South Carolina. 
Jones, who had seemed sluggish the last few days, felt a tingling 
sensation in her feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The trainer told Wise that Jones could not play that night. The  
coach's gut response: Can't we just loosen the tape? This is my 
starting middle blocker. She wouldn't miss a game for anything. 
</P>
<P>
	Within 24 hours, Jones was in the hospital being tested for a  
variety of illnesses, including cancer and multiple sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the virus was spreading, moving from her feet to her  
torso to her arms. Eventually, a related disease called Bell's 
palsy paralyzed the muscles in her face, rendering her unable to 
blink, smile or convey any expression to the dozens of teammates, 
coaches and friends who flooded the hospital room each day. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedridden, unable to walk or smile, Jones was already thinking  
about a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like I've always been training for something,'' Jones  
said. ``It would be so foreign for me, as an athlete brought up to 
give 100 percent all the time and not supposed to give up, to not 
try. Hard work. You give it all the time. You can't just turn it 
off like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rehabilitation went slowly. One of the first days out of the  
hospital, it took her, with the help of friends, nearly two hours 
to get up the stairs to her second-floor apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	The struggles, emotional and physical, continued.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was one of the strongest people on my team and all of the  
sudden, I needed help walking,'' Jones said. ``When you've never 
been sick before and you have to rely on other people to help you 
walk across the room, it's humbling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the rehab progressed and the muscles strengthened, Jones soon  
learned her volleyball skills were still there. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the 1998 season approached, she was a better player.  
And not just physically. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had never really been able to relax and enjoy playing,'' she  
said. ``An attitude like that not only affects you, it affects 
everyone around you. After this, it was just like, it's not worth 
it. It was not worth all the energy I wasted getting so upset with 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones became a better server, a better hitter, an improved  
player. She set career highs in almost every statistical category. 
</P>
<P>
	She fulfilled the goal Wise sets for every player who comes to  
her program -- make the senior season the best. She was placed on 
the All-Southeastern Conference second team and helped the Gators 
return to the Final Four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, you have to be surprised by something like this,''  
Wise said. ``But she's one of the hardest workers I've ever seen. I 
always knew that if coming back could be accomplished through hard 
work, there was no doubt Jeni would be back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the former  
president who once called himself Mexico's favorite villain, met 
expressions of almost visceral hatred Sunday while on his first 
trip to Mexico after four years of self-imposed exile. 
</P>
<P>
	In a near-unanimous show of disapproval, Mexicans vented their  
anger against Salinas, who left the country in disgrace in March 
1995, three months after the end of his six-year presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	He is widely blamed for the collapse of the Mexican peso three  
weeks after he left office, sending Mexico into an economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a public-relations effort, Salinas gave interviews to  
Mexico's two TV networks and offered a press conference, but his 
attempts to defend his image appeared to have failed. 
</P>
<P>
	At the press conference Saturday, he said that a ``tenacious''  
four-year media campaign had been waged against him. 
</P>
<P>
	He told reporters on Saturday he had planned to leave Sunday  
morning. However he apparently changed plans. Local radio stations 
reported he was still in Mexico City Sunday night, attending a 
family gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Federal anti-narcotics agents raided 176  
properties -- including luxurious antique-furnished homes -- 
belonging to imprisoned bosses of the Cali drug cartel, authorities 
said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In operations that began last week, agents took control of  
houses, ranches, apartments and offices in 11 cities belonging to 
convicted drug traffickers Gilberto and Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rodriguez brothers were caught by police in 1995 and  
sentenced to 10 and 20 years in jail respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	The properties -- with an estimated value of $14.8 million -- had  
been registered in the name of third parties, said the DAS state 
security agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia enacted sweeping asset forfeiture legislation in 1996  
that allowed authorities to seize properties belonging to convicted 
drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- An armed gang posing as visitors to a  
Brazilian prison overpowered two guards Sunday and allowed 60 of 66 
inmates inside to flee, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gang of four pulled out guns as the guards opened the main  
gates at visiting time, detective Elias Kobachi said by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Some escapees fled in six cars they stole from where they were  
parked near the prison in Sumare, 110 miles northwest of Sao Paulo, 
she said. Only three inmates were immediately recaptured. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a week ago, in the biggest prison break in Brazil's  
history, 315 inmates fled a prison near Sao Jose dos Campos, in Sao 
Paulo state. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, some 2,200 inmates have escaped from prisons  
and precinct jails in the state. In 1998, the total was 5,888, 
according to police figures. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil is getting ready to offer  
sections of Latin America's largest country for exploration to 
foreign oil companies after the breakup of a 46-year state 
monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the world's biggest oil companies are to bid for 27  
potential oil and gas sites at a massive auction Tuesday and 
Wednesday. Among 37 bidders are Shell, Esso, Texaco and Mobil. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first auction of its kind since the state-owned  
Petrobras' monopoly was abolished almost four years ago. Petrobras 
will participate at the auction and may form partnerships with 
foreign firms. 
</P>
<P>
	David Zylberstztajn, director of the Brazil's National Oil  
Agency, the industry regulator, predicts that $15 billion to $20 
billion will be invested in Brazil over five years following the 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A leading Venezuelan historian on  
Sunday called for the armed forces to intervene if President Hugo 
Chavez uses a constituent assembly to dissolve Congress and the 
Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, the leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt, has said that  
an assembly to be elected July 25 to rewrite Venezuela's 
constitution should dissolve the other branches of government 
because they are corrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	But historian Jorge Olavarria, who Sunday officially announced  
his candidacy for the election, said that would be the equivalent 
of a coup, in effect giving Chavez dictatorial powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez's leftist Patriotic Pole coalition is expected to  
dominate the assembly. He argues that the assembly will have the 
right to shut down Congress and the courts, which he says would be 
replaced by institutions created by the assembly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
