<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O's Ripken Has Five-Hit Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Baltimore's Cal Ripken had his first five-hit  
game in more than 14 years Sunday night against the Braves, 
including two homers that moved him past Johnny Bench and Graig 
Nettles into 32nd place on the career list. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was 5-for-5 after a seventh-inning double gave him six  
RBIs on the night, raising his average to .324. It was the fifth 
time in his career that he had five hits in a game, but the first 
since May 5, 1985 at Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	His first homer, a three-run shot, capped a five-run opening  
inning for the Orioles. He added a two-run homer in the fourth to 
stretch Baltimore's lead to 11-0, drawing a standing, towel-waving 
ovation from the Atlanta fans as he crossed home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles third baseman, best-known for his record playing  
streak, now has 391 homers in his career, breaking from tie with 
Johnny Bench (389) and moving past Nettles (390) as well. Next on 
the list: Joe Carter with 396. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken has 17 two-homer games in his career, the last coming at  
Detroit on Sept. 15, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the homers and run-scoring double, Ripken also  
had singles in the third and sixth innings as the Orioles built a 
20-1 lead by the eighth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
