<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Desert Waves Wins King Edward Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Desert Waves, a 9-year-old gelding who was  
supposed to be the pacesetter, surprised the field by winning the 
$276,250 King Edward Breeders' Cup Handicap at Woodbine on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of Alysheba covered 1 1/8 miles on the turf in 1:46 2-5 and  
finished a length in front of Crown Attorney. Down the Aisle was 
another 1 1/4 lengths back in third in the field of seven horses 3 and 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first win for Desert Waves since Aug. 31, 1997, when  
he also beat Down the Aisle and Crown Attorney in the 1 1/2-mile 
Niagara Handicap at Woodbine. 
</P>
<P>
	Desert Waves returned $10.60, 4.50 and 2.60. Crown Attorney paid  
$4.50 and $2.30, while Down the Aisle was $2.20 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``He ran a really big race today,'' jockey Neil Poznansky said  
of Desert Waves. ``We got off real easy in the fractions part and 
when I asked him down the lane, he really kicked off. There wasn't 
much speed in the race and we got away with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $165,750 purse pushed Desert Waves' career earnings to  
$1,217,029. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
