<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	US Fears Russian Problem in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials are concerned that confusion  
over Russia's role in postwar Kosovo could undermine NATO's effort 
to take an evenhanded approach to emptying the province of Serb 
troops and securing the return of ethnic Albanian refugees to their 
shattered villages. NATO's plan, based on Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic's agreement to withdraw his military and allow 
an international force into Kosovo as peacekeepers, now must be 
adjusted to account for Russia's surprise decision to put troops 
into Kosovo without coordinating with the Western alliance. Russia 
has traditional ties to the Serbs, who are a minority in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	State Dept. Sends Mission to China  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior State Department official is going to  
Beijing with a report on the accidental bombing of the Chinese 
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and a goal of putting strained 
U.S.-China relations back on course. Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright said Sunday that Undersecretary Thomas Pickering and other 
administration officials will again tell the Chinese that the May 7 
bombing, which killed three Chinese citizens, was a ``tragic 
accident.'' They were leaving Monday. Pickering will also stress 
that the United States believes the relationship with China is an 
important one ``that needs to get beyond this,'' Albright said on 
NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Coles Resigns From Sydney Committee  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Phil Coles resigned from the Sydney  
2000 Organizing Committee on Monday but retained his seat on the 
IOC, Olympic officials announced. The compromise deal was offered 
by the International Olympic Committee executive board in a bid to 
close the five-month controversy swirling around the Australian IOC 
member. Coles -- who was already censured in March for his role in 
the Salt Lake City scandal -- had been under the threat of expulsion 
from the IOC for further alleged ethical misconduct. 

</P>
<P>
	Talks Begin Between Automakers, UAW  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- National labor talks between Detroit's automakers  
and the United Auto Workers begin this week in the midst of 
record-breaking sales that have left General Motors Corp., Ford 
Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG flush with cash. The triennial 
negotiations kick off Sunday with ceremonial handshakes over the 
main bargaining table at Ford headquarters. Similar ceremonies are 
set for Tuesday at DaimlerChrysler and Wednesday at GM. The health 
of the U.S. auto industry and the costly lessons learned from last 
year's devastating UAW strikes against GM decrease the chance for a 
walkout after this year's contracts expire Sept. 14, industry 
analysts say. 

</P>
<P>
	Qwest Bids $55B for Telecom Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Qwest Communications International Inc. is  
making a bold $55 billion bid to acquire U S West Inc. and Frontier 
Corp. The unsolicited bids announced Sunday aim to break up the two 
companies' agreements to be acquired by Global Crossing Inc. 
Denver-based Qwest, the nation's fourth-largest long-distance 
telephone company, also offers Internet and data communications 
services to businesses and consumers. The deal would give Qwest a 
piece of the local phone markets in 14 western states with the 
addition of the Denver-based Baby Bell U S West. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Fear E-Mail Virus Mutations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a weekend of scouring their computers for  
the latest e-mail virus to bombard the Internet, systems managers 
are bracing for a new work week and the threat of new infections 
when workers log on. The Worm.Explore.Zip virus, which is 
transmitted via e-mail, has struck thousands of machines, but so 
far hasn't spread as widely as the Melissa virus that hit in late 
March. 

</P>
<P>
	'Austin Powers' Bests 'Star Wars'  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me''  
opened with a gross of nearly $54.7 million to blast ``The Phantom 
Menace'' out of first place, according to industry estimates 
Sunday. The ``Star Wars'' prequel continued to pack in audiences, 
bringing in $25.4 million to bring the film near the $300 million 
mark after just four weeks. ``Austin Powers 2'' has far exceeded 
industry expectations, collecting more in its first three days than 
the original made in its entire theatrical run. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Slightly Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices rose Monday. The Nikkei gained  
107.00 points to finish the morning session at 17,305.55. 

</P>
<P>
	White Sox 6, Cubs 4  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Mike Caruso hit his first homer of the season and  
Ray Durham had four hits for a second straight game as the Chicago 
White Sox beat the Chicago Cubs 6-4 Sunday, sweeping their 
crosstown rivals in a game delayed more than three hours by rain. 
The two teams will play again July 9-11 at Comiskey Park. Durham, 
who says he wants to sweep both series against the Cubs, was almost 
unstoppable, going 9-of-14 in the series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
