<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Negotiate Kosovo Roles  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the first substantial U.S. ground forces  
entered Kosovo, administration officials reported progress today on 
a deal that would allow the Russian military to play a peacekeeping 
role without undermining NATO control. President Clinton and 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin agreed their generals should work 
out details for the first 200 or so Russian troops that already are 
in Kosovo while talks continue on command arrangements for a larger 
contingent, a White House spokesman said. The lead Russian troops 
arrived yesterday in Pristina ahead of alliance forces. They 
blocked NATO from reinforcing British troops at the airport. 

</P>
<P>
	Aid Workers Follow Troops to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Aid workers armed with enough flour  
to bake 45,000 loaves of bread and thousands of ready-to-eat meals 
rolled into Kosovo today, following rifle-toting soldiers in the 
second stage of the region's peace plan. While the NATO force is to 
rebuild law and order in Kosovo, the aid workers are to help 
reconstruct civilian life. Eventually, that will mean restoring a 
court system, municipal administrations, even holding elections. 
The humanitarian convoy included 50 trucks loaded with food, 
blankets, bottled water, tents and plastic sheeting that will be 
distributed over the next few days. 

</P>
<P>
	Europeans Vote for New Parliament  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Overshadowed by events in Kosovo, a  
quiet campaign for seats in the European Union's assembly wrapped 
up Sunday with voting in 11 nations. Voters continued to show 
apathy. Vote counting began in all 15 nations after balloting 
ended. Final results would take until Monday, perhaps Tuesday. 
Turnout for European Parliament elections has declined from 63 
percent in the first ballot in 1979 to 57 percent in 1994 and it 
seemed likely this year's participation would be even lower. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Fear E-Mail Virus Mutations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a weekend of scouring their computers for  
the latest e-mail virus to bombard the Internet, systems managers 
are bracing for a new work week and the threat of new infections 
when workers log on. The Worm.Explore.Zip virus, which is 
transmitted via e-mail, has struck thousands of machines, but so 
far hasn't spread as widely as the Melissa virus that hit in late 
March. 

</P>
<P>
	Qwest Bids $55B for Telecom Cos.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a bold move to bust their agreement to merge  
with Global Crossing Inc. and create a telecommunications 
powerhouse, Qwest Communications International Inc. made a $55 
billion offer today to acquire U S West Inc. and Frontier Corp. The 
deal would give Qwest a piece of the local phone markets in 14 
western states with the addition of Baby Bell U S West and 
strengthen Qwest's long distance business with the addition of 
Frontier, the No. 5 long distance company. 

</P>
<P>
	'Austin Powers' Bests 'Star Wars'  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,''  
the swinging sequel to the surprise 1997 comedy hit, opened with a 
gross of nearly $54.7 million to blast ``The Phantom Menace'' out 
of first place, according to industry estimates today. The ``Star 
Wars'' prequel did continue to pack in audiences, bringing in $25.4 
million to bring the film near the $300 million mark after just 
four weeks. ``Austin Powers 2'' has far exceeded industry 
expectations, collecting more in its first three days than the 
original made in its entire theatrical run. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Trading in Tokyo was subdued early on as investors  
awaited further clues on the direction of the Japanese and U.S. 
economies. The Nikkei Stock Average gained 6.79 points to 
17,205.34. 

</P>
<P>
	Derby Winner Silver Charm Retires  
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Silver Charm, the 1997 Kentucky Derby and  
Preakness winner, has been retired after a fourth-place finish in a 
stakes race at Churchill Downs. The 5-year-old horse will start a 
career as a stallion. Silver Charm retires in third place on the 
thoroughbred career earnings list behind Cigar and Skip Away. 

</P>
<P>
	Angels' Olivares Hits Four Batters  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The Angels' Omar Olivares hit four  
batters with pitches today in Anaheim's game against the Arizona 
Diamondbacks, tying a major league record. He became the 19th 
pitcher to hit four batters in a game, but the second Angels' 
pitcher in three weeks. Anaheim's Steve Sparks hit four Tampa Bay 
batters on May 22. Olivares hit Andy Fox in the third inning, Dave 
Dellucci in the fifth, Kelly Stinnett in the sixth and Dellucci 
again in the seventh. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
