<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Frenchman Wins Piano Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Joel Holoubek, a French coin dealer,  
outplayed 89 other pianists to win the International Piano 
Competition for Outstanding Amateurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Holoubek, one of six finalists, thrilled a packed auditorium at  
Texas Christian University on Sunday with pieces by Ravel and 
Dutilleux. 
</P>
<P>
	He won $2,000, regular seats at the prestigious Van Cliburn  
International Piano Competition and a chance to play with an 
orchestra in Paris sometime before 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	While Holoubek took home the top prize, Alexandre Bodak, a  
French physician, was the audience favorite. He won a collection of 
piano music on compact discs. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition featured performers from nine countries. It was  
sponsored by the Van Cliburn Foundation, the same organization that 
runs the main piano competition every four years. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the first time amateurs have competed. Only those 30 or  
older who are not professional pianists or piano teachers could 
participate. The headline event usually includes pianists younger 
than 30 who are on the path of a musical career. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
