<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O's Ripken Has First Six-Hit Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Orioles' Cal Ripken had the first six-hit  
game of his career -- the first ever by a Baltimore player -- against 
the Braves on Sunday night, including two homers that moved him 
past Johnny Bench and Graig Nettles into 32nd place on the career 
list. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was 6-for-6 with six RBIs, raising his average to .331.  
He had five previous five-hit games, but none since May 5, 1985 at 
Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	His first homer, a three-run shot, capped a five-run opening  
inning for the Orioles. He added a two-run homer in the fourth to 
stretch Baltimore's lead to 11-0, drawing a standing, towel-waving 
ovation from the Atlanta fans as he crossed home plate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles third baseman, best-known for his record playing  
streak, now has 391 homers in his career, breaking from tie with 
Johnny Bench (389) and moving past Nettles (390) as well. Next on 
the list: Joe Carter with 396. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken has 17 two-homer games in his career, the last coming at  
Detroit on Sept. 15, 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the homers and a run-scoring double in the  
seventh, Ripken also had singles in the third, sixth and ninth 
innings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
