<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 11:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expansion Prompts Worker Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Unemployment and inflation are at their lowest  
in three decades, two economic facts that have helped cause the 
worker shortage now plaguing American businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Why is this happening?  
</P>
<P>
	Call it Alan Greenspan's Grand Experiment.  
</P>
<P>
	Inflation has remained docile despite strong economic growth.  
That has prompted Greenspan and his colleagues at the Federal 
Reserve to let the unemployment rate fall far below levels which 
used to trigger rising wage demands. Higher wages are usually a 
major contributor to inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Fed feared inflation, it would raise interest rates to  
slow the economy. Because interest rates remain low, economic 
growth has continued at a strong pace, driving the jobless rate 
even lower and making qualified workers more difficult to find. 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, America is enjoying 8 1/2-years of uninterrupted economic  
growth -- the longest stretch in peacetime history. Long periods of 
growth push the unemployment rate still lower as employers search 
harder to fill new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists still believe there is a threshold of employment  
where workers become so scarce that their demands for higher pay 
will finally spur inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	But they now admit this threshold is far below the 6 percent  
unemployment rate they once agreed on. Why this has occurred is the 
subject of heated debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic optimists believe there's been a fundamental change in  
the U.S. economy because of the billions of dollars businesses have 
spent on computers and other productivity-enhancing equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Productivity -- the amount of output per hour of work -- has been  
rising over the past three years at close to a 2 percent average 
rate. Higher productivity means employers can pay workers more 
without raising the cost of their products. 
</P>
<P>
	Pessimists believe that the increase in productivity so far has  
been too small to really influence inflation much. They credit the 
combination of extremely low inflation and high employment to a 
host of temporary factors. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of these factors relate to recessions in Asia and other  
regions which have rewarded American consumers with falling prices 
for a variety of imported goods -- everything from gasoline to 
autos. 
</P>
<P>
	There are signs that good news is coming to an end. Consumer  
prices took a big upward leap in April and financial markets are 
bracing for the Fed to start raising interest rates, which will 
slow the economy and send unemployment higher. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the betting at present is that the Fed will be able to  
accomplish a soft-landing, in which the economy will slow enough to 
keep inflation under control but not enough to cause a recession. 
That feat was last accomplished in 1994. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 11:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts Expect Tight Credit Policy / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If the Federal Reserve takes a step to tighten  
its credit policy later this month, it won't catch anybody on Wall 
Street by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the Fed embarks on a sustained strategy of pushing  
interest rates higher over the next several months, that might be a 
different story. 
</P>
<P>
	As the yield on long-term Treasury bonds climbed above 6 percent  
last week for the first time in more than a year, analysts on the 
Street said it was an odds-on bet that the Fed would opt for higher 
short-term rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``By now, U.S. credit markets are pricing in a near certainty  
that the Fed will raise interest rates by 25 basis points (or 
hundredths of a percentage point) on June 30,'' said Dan Bernstein 
at the Westport, Conn., money-management firm of Bridgewater 
Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernstein pointed out that a July futures contract for federal  
funds, or overnight loans between banks, recently traded at just 
under 5 percent, nearly a quarter-point more than the Fed's current 
target of 4.75 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Although rising rates have prompted some sporadic selling in the  
stock market in recent weeks, most analysts argue that there isn't 
any cause for alarm. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a rate hike, investors should not be overly  
concerned,'' says Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist at the St. 
Louis-based brokerage firm of Edward Jones. ``Historically, the 
stock market on average has been higher after one or two rate 
increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``The greatest risk to the market is a Fed that waits too long  
to kill the inflation threat, then is forced to follow through with 
multiple rate hikes in an effort to play catch-up. Once the 
inflation beast has escaped, it takes considerably more effort to 
corral it and kill it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Hoey, chief economist and research director at the  
Dreyfus Corp., the big New York money management firm, says he 
distinguishes between ``full stop'' Fed tightenings designed to 
rein in a runaway economy, and ``tap-on-the-brakes'' tightenings 
intended more as precautionary measures. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I think we'll see is a tap-on-the-brakes tightening --  
nothing too dramatic,'' Hoey said at a meeting with reporters last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the world economy, the news is relatively good. The  
prospects are for a sustainable world expansion.'' In the United 
States, he added, ``it is probable that the cyclical lows in 
inflation have already occurred. However, the coming inflation 
cycle is likely to be relatively mild.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From this kind of talk, it's evident that Wall Streeters don't  
want to see persistent bad news on inflation AFTER the Fed has 
taken steps to tighten credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have kept their bull market going even as rates on  
30-year Treasury bonds have climbed from about 4.7 percent last 
October to 6 percent now. Very few analysts, though, are looking 
for any significant further increase in long-term rates. So further 
pressure on the bond market could spell trouble for stocks as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Lavery, a consultant to Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., says a move to  
tighter credit is likely ``not because the Fed believes that any 
meaningful cyclical re-escalation of inflation is a prospect, but 
in order to maintain credibility in the eyes of the ultimate 
policeman of the financial markets, the bond market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Concludes Skrainka: ``We continue to believe that there are  
powerful forces keeping inflation in check: Strong labor 
productivity and an abundance of almost everything with the 
exception of labor. 
</P>
<P>
	``With very few inflationary pressures in the pipeline, the Fed  
is unlikely to engage in a series of rate hikes. A more likely 
scenario is one little tap on the brakes, just to make sure the 
economy does not travel at an unsafe speed.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
