<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Albright: Serb Withdrawal Going Well  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright says the  
Serb military withdrawal from Kosovo is going smoothly. Albright 
said that already some 11,000 Serbian troops and police had left 
Kosovo and that 35 percent of their armored vehicles are out, as 
are 15 percent of their tanks. NATO has estimated there were about 
40,000 Serb troops in Kosovo when the alliance suspended its 
airstrikes last Thursday. Albright also said she was confident that 
differences with Russia over the surprise entry of Russian troops 
ahead of NATO peacekeepers would be worked out. 

</P>
<P>
	1st Big U.S. Unit Enters Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The first big unit of U.S. Army  
troops has entered Kosovo from Macedonia. The Pentagon says several 
hundred soldiers in tanks and Bradley fighting vehicles are heading 
north toward the capital of Pristina. About 1,000 Marines are also 
set to enter Kosovo. In eastern Pristina, NATO soldiers in several 
armored personnel carriers were trying to work their way around 
roadblocks set up by Serbs near the suburb of Sofali. After being 
turned away at two roadblocks, the British troops were trying to 
get in through a back road. Meanwhile, there are reports of Serb 
forces setting ethnic Albanian houses afire as they retreat ahead 
of advancing NATO troops. 

</P>
<P>
	State Department Sending China Envoy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States is dispatching an envoy to  
China in hopes of repairing relations damaged by NATO's accidental 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia. Chinese officials 
have demanded a full accounting of the incident and want those 
responsible punished. Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering will 
lead a team of administration officials departing tomorrow for 
Beijing. Other matters have chilled ties, including allegations of 
Chinese theft of U.S. nuclear secrets. 

</P>
<P>
	India Claims Capture of Kashmir Peak  
</P>
<P>
	DRAS, India (AP) -- Indian troops captured a key mountain peak in  
Kashmir from guerrillas today, officials said, following an 
all-night battle that began as India and Pakistan ended 
unsuccessful talks to end the fighting. The summit of Tololing Peak 
is near a cease-fire line with Pakistan and overlooks Indian's 
northern highway. That capture and what officers said was the 
anticipated seizure of a nearby peak would help secure a vulnerable 
stretch of Indian highway that has been under constant bombardment 
from artillery units inside of Pakistan. India blames the month-old 
hostilities on Pakistan, accusing it of sending hundreds of 
soldiers and mercenaries over the cease-fire line that divides the 
Himalayan territory between the two powers. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Returns to Site of 1979 Mass  
</P>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II returned in triumph  
today to the square where he began his crusade against communism 20 
years ago, telling 1 million of his countrymen that God had 
answered their prayers. The 79-year-old pontiff looked and sounded 
tired. His words in 1979 became a rallying cry against repression, 
inspiring the Solidarity movement that toppled communism 10 years 
later. During the Mass, the pope beatified 108 Poles killed during 
World War II, the latest in a series of Poles honored as martyrs 
during the trip. 

</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Builds in Atlantic  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Tropical Storm Arlene, the first of the season,  
built to 60 mph winds today and experts said it could strengthen 
even more as it spins deep in the Atlantic. A forecaster said the 
storm might threaten Bermuda at some point. At 11 a.m. EDT, 
Arlene's center was near 29.2 north latitude and 58.4 west 
longitude, or about 430 miles southeast of Bermuda and 1,100 miles 
from the mid-Atlantic coast. Storm-force winds of 39 mph extended 
up to 115 miles from the center, which was drifting northwest near 
2 mph. 

</P>
<P>
	Bugner Fights Again at 49  
</P>
<P>
	GOLD COAST, Australia (AP) -- Forty-nine year-old Joe Bugner won  
what he said was the final fight of 32-year career today when 
American Levi Billups was disqualified for repeated low blows in 
the ninth round. Bugner twice went the distance with Muhammad Ali, 
once in a world title fight in 1975. He won the British, European, 
Commonwealth, Australian and the World Boxing Federation 
heavyweight titles at various times in his career. Bugner's record 
is listed at 69 victories, 13 losses and a draw. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
