<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Ford's Theatre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tap dancing, gospel, country music, jazz and  
an operatic version of the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic'' were on 
the bill for President Clinton Sunday night at the taping of a 
television special honoring Ford's Theatre. 
</P>
<P>
	The performers, the president and his wife, Hillary Rodham  
Clinton, came together to honor the theater at which President 
Lincoln spent many enjoyable nights during the Civil War and where 
he was assassinated. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's Theatre, Clinton said, ``is a profoundly important part  
of our history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it always is at Ford's, the box in which Lincoln and his  
party were seated the night of his assassination in April 1865 was 
draped with flags and bunting. 
</P>
<P>
	The gala is the 20th television tribute to Ford's, which  
reopened as a theater in 1968 after being used for other purposes 
for 103 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Performers included a 13-year-old Welsh soprano, Charlotte  
Church, who sang ``Amazing Grace''; country-western singer Alan 
Jackson; jazz vocalist Diana Krall and 9-year-old tap dancer 
Cartier Anthony Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyric soprano Kathleen Battle ended the show with a performance  
of the ``Battle Hymn of the Republic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't help thinking when Kathleen Battle came out and  
sang the 'Battle Hymn of the Republic' that it was at this theater 
that Abraham Lincoln kept up his love of music,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said that as the Lincoln funeral train crossed the  
country on its way to the late president's home at Springfield, 
Ill. the bands at every stop played the song. 
</P>
<P>
	They understood, he said, that it represented Lincoln's cause  
and his character. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
