<DOCNO> APW19990613.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Tries To Polish His Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's aides catalogued  
every phone call, every meeting and every note passed between their 
boss and Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin over the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	It's proof, they let reporters know, that their guy commanded  
trust abroad and had the stuff to be commander in chief at home. 
</P>
<P>
	That the Serbs -- nudged by Chernomyrdin, who was nudged by Gore  
-- accepted U.S. demands and retreated from Kosovo is a plus for the 
vice president as he formally launches his campaign this week for 
the top job, Democrats and Republicans agree. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kosovo crisis, and its potential to erupt into a ground war  
with U.S. casualties, reminded American voters that foreign policy 
counts, ``that the United States is going to be in the business of 
using force overseas and a president is going to have to know how 
to do that,'' said Robert Kagan, a veteran of President Reagan's 
State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the general perception is that Kosovo was a success, it may  
be perceived that Gore has the experience in leadership around the 
world,'' Kagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	But diplomacy is tricky business, and the Kosovo story -- moving  
to the chapter where nearly 30 nations send armed peacekeepers into 
the volatile province -- is not yet finished. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at his dining room table that Gore laid out for  
Chernomyrdin, the go-between with Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic, the United States' bottom line. The scene won Gore 
credit from President Clinton for keeping fragile U.S.-Russian 
relations ``on track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president was eager last week to showcase his prowess  
with the Russians. But, since his daughter's Harvard graduation 
ceremony fell on the day of the Serb retreat, he left the first 
victory lap to Clinton. By the time Gore made his morning-after 
round of network TV interviews, surprise Russian troop movements 
overnight into Serbia robbed him of the chance to strut his 
commander-in-chief stuff. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, the -- we didn't know they were going to go right  
there,'' Gore stammered on ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo is perhaps a plus more for the liabilities that it  
diminishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since he's the quasi-incumbent, he won't now be in position to  
have to defend an unpopular war into the winter just as the 
campaign is heating up,'' said Richard Haass, who was a top 
National Security Council official in the Bush administration. 
</P>
<P>
	One top Democratic strategist, demanding anonymity, called  
Kosovo the single most difficult foreign policy issue of the 
Clinton administration and acknowledged that if it had hung around 
for the next 18 months, it could have been ``deadly'' for Gore's 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore's White House staff diligently reported to  
journalists a running ``tick tock'' of the vice president's 
diplomatic work on Kosovo, his campaign aides insisted they were 
above considering the political implications. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just not looking at it in that context,'' said deputy  
campaign chairman Marla Romash. ``If the peace is real and if our 
optimism turns to reality, it's good for America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peace immediately dulled the bite of Republican opponents  
Elizabeth Dole and Arizona Sen. John McCain, who won attention for 
their fledgling campaigns by harshly questioning the Clinton-Gore 
team's resolve to face down Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can argue about whether we should have become involved in  
this conflict and about how we prosecuted the war, but we should 
all agree that our victory is very good news for the United States, 
NATO and for the world,'' McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	All Dole had to say was that Clinton should have been tougher on  
Milosevic from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	With peace, candidates win back the chance to talk about Social  
Security, school safety and the economy -- domestic issues that 
pollsters say will be more decisive in the 2000 race. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain pollster Bill McInturff said that may be the biggest plus  
for Gore. ``If you're the incumbent vice president running for 
office, you want people focusing on what's happening in the country 
because for the most part, people feel things have gone good for 
the past six years,'' he said. ``You don't want them focusing on 
how screwed up things are around the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And so, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, in announcing his candidacy  
in Iowa on Saturday, touched implicitly what could be the rawest 
remaining foreign-policy nerve for Gore -- allegations of overall 
incompetence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will rebuild our military power because a dangerous world  
still requires a sharpened sword. I will move quickly to defend our 
people and our allies. I will have a foreign policy with a touch of 
iron,'' Bush pledged. 
</P>
<P>
	Potential pitfalls do remain for Gore: a disaster in military  
readiness; another face-off with Saddam Hussein in Iraq; a 
political or financial meltdown in Russia; another flare-up of 
nuclear tensions in South Asia or more damning evidence of letting 
U.S. secrets slip to the Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Iraq comes back -- and I don't think Saddam all of a  
sudden gave up building weapons of mass destruction just because we 
stopped paying attention -- and when China remains an issue, a win 
in Kosovo doesn't cancel those out,'' said Kagan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 11:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers Mull New Car Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pete Peterson remembers all too well how his  
steel industry lost its grip on beverage cans and handed the market 
to aluminum in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	So as auto companies facing tighter environmental standards look  
for ways to make lighter cars that burn less fuel, Peterson is 
determined not to let history repeat itself. 
</P>
<P>
	The competition is fierce as automakers consider a new mix of  
materials in tomorrow's cars. Aluminum bills itself as a lighter 
alternative to steel, forcing steel to spend millions of dollars 
simply to protect its turf. 
</P>
<P>
	``We sat back when the aluminum can came around and thought they  
couldn't possibly succeed,'' said Peterson, head of the auto 
marketing group at U.S. Steel. ``We lost that whole market to them 
because we didn't take the threat seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson oversaw the Pittsburgh steel maker's marketing division  
for can-production products when aluminum began cutting into 
steel's dominance, even though the steel industry thought it had a 
better, cheaper product. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, aluminum is the material used to make virtually  
every can in the United States for beer and carbonated beverages. 
</P>
<P>
	In autos, aluminum has seen its use double in the past decade  
and set a usage record in the 1999 model year. The gains largely 
have been in the engine and other under-the-hood parts, but cars 
with aluminum exteriors have begun emerging. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without sacrificing safety, aluminum allows manufacturers to  
reduce the mass of autos,'' said J. Stephen Larkin, president of 
The Aluminum Association, a Washington-based trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	He said an aluminum car can be 22 percent larger than a steel  
car of the same weight -- an important attribute given motorists' 
growing affinity for large sport utility vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Audi, Honda and Plymouth are among the manufacturers that have  
introduced aluminum-intensive cars, although those models are 
luxury or specialty cars sold at a premium. 
</P>
<P>
	Costs and the need for different manufacturing and repair  
techniques have held back aluminum's wider usage in cars. Plastics 
and other materials face similar challenges. Steel now has a 55 
percent market share in autos, compared with about 7 percent each 
for aluminum and plastics. 
</P>
<P>
	To prevent a recurrence of the erosion that took place with  
cans, the steel industry has spent more than $20 million over the 
past half-decade to develop a new steel auto body that is 25 
percent lighter than the typical body. The new frame uses 
higher-strength steel and new manufacturing techniques. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry is working to lighten other auto parts as well,  
effectively raising the standards that competing materials will 
have to meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to be outdone, aluminum companies this month announced a  
joint venture with the nation's biggest automakers to find ways to 
cut costs and improve manufacturing techniques, thereby cutting 
into steel's incumbency advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a real horse race,'' said David Cole,  
director of the Office for the Study of Automotive Transportation 
at the University of Michigan. ``Just because you're in the cab 
driver's seat now doesn't mean things won't change and you'll be 
the winner forever. The steel industry is running very scared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The research on lighter cars is driven in part by a  
government-industry challenge to develop by 2004 a car that can get 
80 miles from a gallon of gas. Automakers are also preparing for 
future government pollution-control requirements expected to be 
even more restrictive than current standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Autos represent a large market for both steel and aluminum, and  
both industries are fiercely jockeying for an edge even though car 
makers expect future vehicles to contain some mixture of steel and 
aluminum, as well as other materials. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that people tend to think of this as an  
either-or proposition,'' said Chris Terry of the U.S. Council for 
Automotive Research, a partnership of DaimlerChrysler, Ford and 
General Motors. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the number of cars produced each year is growing, all  
materials are likely to gain even if single-car percentages change, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Underscoring the intensity of the rivalry, the aluminum and the  
steel industries have battled in recent weeks through press 
releases, with each claiming environmental benefits over the other. 
</P>
<P>
	The aluminum industry has said that for every pound of aluminum  
use, replacing two pounds of steel in autos, can save 20 pounds of 
carbon dioxide emission over the lifetime of that vehicle. The 
steel industry countered that any savings would not come for 
decades because making aluminum is dirtier than making steel. Each 
industry faulted the assumptions used in the other's studies. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry does acknowledge some of aluminum's  
environmental benefits, while the aluminum companies do concede 
their product costs more than steel on a per-pound basis. So both 
industries are working to improve on their advantages. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason why the industry is investing as heavily as it is  
in new designs, new technology and new products is we have got to 
be a moving target,'' said Andrew Sharkey, chief executive of the 
industry trade group, the American Iron and Steel Institute. 
``Steel is the familiar material, and what we're trying to show is 
we've just begun to scratch the surface.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
