<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gas Prices Drop Nearly 3 Cents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMARILLO, Calif. (AP) -- Gasoline prices dropped nearly 3 cents  
per gallon nationwide in the past three weeks, but the decline 
might stall if crude oil prices continue to rise, an industry 
analyst said. 
</P>
<P>
	The national weighted average, including all grades with taxes,  
was $1.1902 per gallon Friday, down 2.78 cents from the previously 
survey on May 21, Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the Lundberg Survey 
of 10,000 stations across the country, said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	A good supply of domestic crude has helped shield American  
motorists from price hikes by OPEC and other oil-producing 
countries. But if crude prices continue to rise, U.S. pump prices 
might level off during the summer driving season, Ms. Lundberg 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas prices dropped for 1 1/2 years until bottoming out in  
mid-February, when the average for all grades was 99.8 cents per 
gallon. That was followed by a hikes in the spring before prices 
topped out at an average of $1.2337 in early May. 
</P>
<P>
	At self-service pumps, the average for regular unleaded on  
Friday was $1.1320, mid-grade averaged $1.2333 and premium $1.3183. 
</P>
<P>
	For full-service, the average was $1.5159 for regular, $1.6031  
for mid-grade and $1.6771 for premium. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 15:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Steve Park picked up where he left off  
last year at Michigan Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	In August 1998, the Northport, N.Y. driver recorded his best  
career finish during the Pepsi 400 -- 11th place. On Sunday, Park 
bettered that with a sixth-place showing in the Kmart 400. That 
even beat team owner Dale Earnhardt's 16th-place finish. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were trying to get a top-10 finish and we almost got a  
top-five finish,'' Park said. ``We were catching up there at the 
end. If we'd had a couple of more pit stops we probably would have 
been a lot better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Park, who started from the 10th position, said his team has  
improved since adding Paul Andrews as crew chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole deal has been different the last four or five  
weeks,'' he said. ``We've had good ingredients with people and cars 
and motors to run well. But we just didn't have the leader to lead 
this team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Its just real nice to be able to go to a Winston Cup race and  
qualify 10th and be able to advance your position and finish sixth. 
I'm really looking forward to the rest of the season now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROLLING ROOKIE*: Rookie Tony Stewart turned in one of his most  
impressive driving performances of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting from the 28th position, Stewart weaved his way to ninth  
place. It was his fifth top-10 finish in his last six races. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a top-10 finish and I should be happy with that, but we  
gave up a couple of positions,'' Stewart said. ``We didn't get all 
the fuel in on our last stop and I had to feather the throttle 
during the entire last run. I think we could have beaten a couple 
of guys if I had been able to go full throttle. I ran out just as 
(race-winner Dale) Jarrett captured the checkered flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A top-10 finish appeared to only be a dream early in the race  
when Geoffrey Bodine and Stewart made contact in Turn 4, causing 
damage to Stewart's right front. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could tell the car wasn't as good after that,'' Stewart  
said. ``I don't know what the deal was.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LONE NON-SURVIVOR*: The lone driver to not finish the race was  
Jimmy Spencer, who was forced out with engine problems after 
completing 159 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	``It blew up real early,'' Spencer said of the motor.  
``Something happened to it real early in the race and we just kept 
riding around trying to get all we could get. It was missing when 
they dropped the green flag, so it evidently gave way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer has failed to finish in five of 14 races this season.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HOPES SEVERED*: Bill Elliott's chance at victory were dashed by  
some debris scattered on the track. 
</P>
<P>
	While running in sixth place on lap 168, some debris on the race  
track came through the bottom of Elliott's car and broke his oil 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we broke an oil line underneath the front,'' said  
Elliott, who finished 41st. ``It just started smoking. We had a 
good car. 
</P>
<P>
	``We needed to be a little bit better, but Jarrett was just  
awesome. We weren't bad compared to (Jeff) Gordon and the rest of 
the guys, but man, it's heartbreaking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott led from laps 22 to 24 and laps 26 to 28. Each time he  
gave up the lead to Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PIT STOPS*: A crowd estimated at a record 160,000 watched  
Sunday's race. ... Five Pontiacs finished in the top 10 -- Ward 
Burton, Bobby Labonte, Ernie Irvan, John Andretti and Stewart. ... 
Darrell Morrow, a crewman for Mark Martin, fell to the ground after 
being hit by an air wrench during an unscheduled pit stop. He 
refused medical treatment and continued with his duties. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
