<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Small Booksellers Struggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Founded in 1872, Lauriat's Booksellers survived  
the Great Fire that wiped out most of the city's downtown that 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	But 127 years later, Lauriat's couldn't stand the heat from  
Amazon.com, barnesandnoble.com and Borders.com. 
</P>
<P>
	As the venerable chain announced plans to liquidate its stores  
last week, booksellers across New England said they are struggling 
to hang onto customers in an era of instant online gratification 
and giant corporate chains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eventually there will be one bookstore and that bookstore will  
be called Amazon.com,'' said a glum Joe Porth, assistant manager of 
the Lauriat's in Copley Plaza. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, he'll be out of work and shoppers will be out of a  
bookstore. The plaza's other bookshop, Rizzoli Bookstore, announced 
plans to leave weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Porth said he sees little hope for smaller booksellers, even  
regional chains, against the onslaught of megastores -- real and 
virtual. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can you find a pharmacy that isn't CVS, a hardware store that  
isn't Home Depot, or a theater that isn't a Sony or a Loews?'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Waterstone's, a popular chain of British bookshops,  
pulled out of the Boston area, closing locations in Faneuil Hall, 
the city's Back Bay neighborhood and the Burlington Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	The loss of smaller chain stores like Lauriat's, Waterstone's  
and Rizzoli mirrors the loss of independent booksellers in the 
region over the past few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Membership in the New England Booksellers Association now hovers  
at 500, down from 535 three years ago, said executive director 
Rusty Drugan. Of those, 225 stores are in Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	To make things worse, the American public bought fewer books  
last year, 1.1 billion compared to 1.2 billion in 1997. Plus, 
online bookstores are getting far more attention than they deserve, 
Drugan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All they have is a database that the independents have had  
access to forever,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Independent stores have books that don't even appear on  
Amazon,'' he added, citing local authors and local publishing 
houses he said were passed over by the virtual bookseller. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller booksellers are finally putting up a fight for their  
corner of virtual book business, with powerful outlets in Harvard 
Square leading the way for the independents. 
</P>
<P>
	WordsWorth Books and the Harvard Book Store have launched their  
own Web sites -- wordsworth.com and harvard.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``Real Books. Real Booksellers. Real Bookstore,'' says  
WordsWorth's site in a dig at online competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	But Amazon.com says it is not to blame for driving little  
bookshops out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only since 1997 have we been considered a serious mainstream  
bookstore, and the unfortunate demise of independent bookstores 
began long before that,'' said spokesman Bill Curry in a telephone 
interview from the company's Seattle headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether online or off-line, the people who are going to  
survive are going to best meet customer needs. The independent 
stores that are thriving are doing just that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Willard Williams, co-owner of New Hampshire-based Toadstool  
Bookshops, said cyberspace can best help his operation by marketing 
the pleasures of visiting a bookshop in person. 
</P>
<P>
	``We as bookstores need to continue trying to make our stores  
more interesting places to be ... we need to tailor our selections 
to what people are really interested in,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drugan agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't do the independent bookstores any good to tell  
people to buy from them just because they're independent,'' he 
said. ``People need to see the connection with their lives ... 
local bookstores supporting local kids, literacy programs and local 
authors.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 18:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qwest Bids $55B for Telecom Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a bid to be among those still standing after  
a wave of consolidation sweeps the telecommunications industry, 
Qwest Communications International Inc. is making a bold $55 
billion bid to acquire U S West Inc. and Frontier Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The unsolicited bids announced Sunday aim to break up the two  
companies' agreements to be acquired by Global Crossing Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Denver-based Qwest is the nation's fourth-largest long-distance  
telephone company also offers Internet and data communications 
services to businesses and consumers. The deal would give Qwest a 
piece of the local phone markets in 14 western states with the 
addition of the Denver-based Baby Bell U S West. It would 
strengthen Qwest's long distance business with the addition of 
Rochester, N.Y.-based Frontier, the No. 5 long-distance company, 
which also has local phone, cellular, paging and Internet 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest is offering $78 a share in stock for U S West and $73 a  
share in cash and stock for Frontier. Qwest would sweeten each bid 
by $2 a share if both companies agree to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Both those bids are higher than Global Crossing's offer to pay  
about $63 a share in stock for both U S West and Frontier in 
separate deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing is a Bermuda-based company with plans to link  
the world's continents with high-speed fiber optic cables. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing stock, however, has fallen 16 percent in recent  
weeks as the companies have had a hard time selling investors on 
the benefits of combining their businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the clear superiority of our offer to the proposed  
Global Crossing merger, we would like to meet with you and your 
advisors as soon as possible,'' wrote Joseph P. Nacchio, Qwest 
chairman and chief executive officer, in letters to the heads of U 
S West and Frontier. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West and Frontier both said they would review the offers and  
declined to comment further. Officials from Global Crossing 
declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet is revolutionizing the telecommunications industry  
and is driving a string of merger bids. Companies are hoping that 
the next generation of high-speed Internet technologies will link 
more homes and businesses, providing a wealth of new opportunities 
to sell goods and provide information and entertainment. These 
hopes have prompted telecom and cable companies to make big bets on 
mergers so they can gain the size and market share that will be 
keys to new profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``These new companies like Qwest and Global Crossing are  
building state-of-the-art fiber optic networks which are the key to 
the future of a communications company, but they don't have the 
customers or revenues yet,'' said Jeffrey Kagan, an independent 
telecom analyst. ``On the other hand, companies like U S West and 
Frontier have the older networks but they have the customers and 
revenue. So it's natural for the two of them to get together,'' 
Kagan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AT&AMP;T Corp. won a bidding war with cable TV company  
Comcast for MediaOne Group Inc., another cable company. AT&AMP;T, the 
nation's largest long distance company, is gambling that television 
cables will also be the way to carry Internet, voice and data 
traffic in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Other telecom companies such as Qwest and U S West are banking  
on an alternative high-speed Internet technology that uses 
traditional telephone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest is successful in its takeover quest, the combined  
company would have revenues of $22 billion in 2000 and serve 31 
million customers. Currently, Qwest has just $2.24 billion in 
revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest estimates the united company could save as much as $11.1  
billion in operating costs and capital investments, and generate up 
to $3.1 billion in sales as it expands local telephone service as 
well as data and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a heady undertaking, and not without risks. Global  
Crossing, or another telephone company, could raise the stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We entered this planning to win,'' Nacchio said in an  
interview. ``That will remain unchanged, irrespective of anyone 
else's entering it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest's offer is accepted by U S West, the company's chairman  
and chief executive officer, Solomon D. Trujillo, would be invited 
to become the vice chairman of Qwest. Trujillo and three other U S 
West directors would also be asked to join Qwest's board. 
</P>
<P>
	For Frontier, Qwest is offering two seats on its board,  
including one for Joseph P. Clayton, Frontier's chief executive 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Rumors that Qwest was eyeing U S West surfaced last month when  
Global Crossing struck its deal with the Baby Bell. But the 
whispers grew louder last week, and U S West's stock rose 56 1/4 cents 
Friday to $54.87 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. Qwest's stock 
gained $1 Friday to $44.87 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The tandem bid for Frontier, however, was quite unexpected.  
Frontier's stock closed Friday down 25 cents to $55.43 3/4, also on 
the Big Board. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 20:00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels' Colangelo Hurt in Debut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Mike Colangelo, making his major league  
debut, was hurt in a collision in the outfield Sunday in the 
seventh inning of the Anaheim Angels' game against Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo was taken to UC Irvine Medical Center with a high back  
injury and an injured left wrist, Angels spokesman Tim Mead said. 
Colangelo was talking and able to move his limbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo, playing left, and center fielder Reggie Williams were  
both running full speed for a fly in the gap hit by Steve Finley. 
Williams caught the ball and immediately crashed into Colangelo, 
who lay on the field for about 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Angels trainers tended to Colangelo, who was placed on an  
immobilizing board for precautionary and taken off the field on a 
medical cart. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo, 22, was just called up from Anaheim's Triple-A  
Edmonton farm team and singled in the first inning. He walked and 
grounded out his next two times up. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hitting .362, with 13 runs scored and nine RBIs in 26  
games at Edmonton. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams remained in the game.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 13:36:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Beats Argentina in Soccer 1-0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Joe-Max Moore scored in the 88th minute and  
Kasey Keller blocked a first-half penalty kick Sunday, leading the 
United States past Argentina 1-0 in an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore, who entered the game as a substitute in the 60th minute  
for a hobbling Eddie Lewis, ran toward the top of the penalty area 
and accepted a backheel feed from Ernie Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Before an RFK Stadium crowd of 40,119, Moore's left-footed shot  
easily beat goalie German Burgos to the upper left corner. It was 
his 19th goal in international competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller made the most critical of his seven saves in the 42nd  
minute after referee Rodrigo Badilla penalized defender C.J. Brown 
of the United States for upending Gustavo Lopez. 
</P>
<P>
	Lopez sent a low shot to Keller's left. Keller tricked him into  
shooting there by stutter-stepping to his right, then gobbling up 
the shot with a quick move the other way. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States improved to 3-1-3 since Bruce Arena took over  
as coach in November 1998. The Americans next play in the FIFA 
Confederations Cup in Mexico in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina, preparing for the Copa America Cup in Paraguay this  
month, tied Mexico 2-2 in Chicago on Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0085 </DOCNO>
