<DOCNO> APW19990613.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 10:29:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pope Returns to Site of 1979 Mass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II returned in triumph  
Sunday to the square where he began his crusade against communism 
20 years ago, telling 1 million of his countrymen that God had 
answered their prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	The 79-year-old pontiff, his head still bandaged from a cut  
received in a fall a day earlier, looked and sounded tired. But his 
words received repeated applause from the attentive crowd, the 
largest since the start of his pilgrimage nine days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The nearly three-hour Mass was held in the former Victory Square  
where -- on his first trip as pope back to his communist homeland in 
1979 -- John Paul ended his homily with a prayer for the Holy Spirit 
to ``renew the face'' of Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	His words became a rallying cry against repression, inspiring  
the Solidarity movement that toppled communism 10 years later. 
</P>
<P>
	``In those difficult times, we asked that his power might be  
poured into the hearts of men and women and that hope might be 
stirred in them,'' John Paul said Sunday. ``Is not all that 
happened at that time in Europe and the world, beginning with our 
own homeland, God's response?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The political, social and economic changes, he said, have  
enabled people and nations ``to see anew the splendor of their own 
dignity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under a giant white dove -- symbolizing the Holy Spirit -- on the  
facade of the Grand Theater, the pope repeated his call for renewal 
to a crowd that included Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and President 
Aleksander Kwasniewski. 
</P>
<P>
	``We support in prayer all efforts of the authorities aimed at  
the good of the nation,'' the pope said, an apparent reference to 
further measures needed to address high unemployment and other 
painful effects of the transition to a free-market economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before leaving, he invoked the prayer of two decades ago,  
imploring the Holy Spirit ``at the threshold of the third 
millennium'' to ``keep descending and constantly renew the face of 
the earth, of this Polish earth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the Mass, the pope beatified 108 Poles killed during  
World War II, the latest in a series of Poles honored as martyrs 
during the trip. They included nuns and priests who helped save 
Jews from the Nazis and seminarians killed at Dachau. 
</P>
<P>
	Two others also were beatified -- Regina Protmann, who began an  
order of nuns in the 16th century devoted to helping the suffering 
and dying, and Edmund Bojanowski, a 19th-century Pole who 
established a congregation of nuns devoted to children and the 
sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Under threatening skies that sprinkled showers once during the  
Mass, more than 350,000 packed the vast square, renamed for World 
War I independence hero Jozef Pilsudski, while hundreds of 
thousands filled nearby streets far from the papal altar. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500 yards away, Zdzislaw Mioduszewski stood with his wife  
and three children, unable to see the pope. ``We could have stayed 
home and watched on television, but we wanted to share the 
experience,'' he explained. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul received three stitches Saturday after slipping at the  
Vatican Embassy in Warsaw. The bandage on his temple was smaller 
Sunday and the pope was able to wear his gold miter again, but the 
Vatican offered no update on his condition. 
</P>
<P>
	His schedule has remained unchanged, with three other events  
planned Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The pope has walked slowly, using a cane, since a 1994 hip  
replacement. He sometimes slurs his speech and his left hand 
trembles, possible symptoms of Parkinson's disease, a progressive 
neurological disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in the crowd recalled a robust John Paul arriving 20 years  
ago for what they described as a vitalizing experience. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a great outburst of euphoria at the end,'' said  
Maria Sciegienko, 64. ``Some were clapping, some were crying. It 
was a very special time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 13-day pilgrimage next takes John Paul to Krakow, where he  
studied for the priesthood and served as archbishop before assuming 
the papacy in 1978. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 10:29:39 </DATE_TIME>
