<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 14:22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TWA, Union Reach Tentative Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Trans World Airlines and its major union  
representing flight attendants, mechanics and other workers reached 
a tentative agreement Sunday on a new contract, possibly averting a 
strike that could have jeopardized the long-struggling company. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Machinists said it would cancel  
the rank-and-file voting that began last week, and then present the 
new contract offer to its members. The union represents 16,000 of 
TWA's 21,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders agreed there would be no work stoppages during the  
monthlong ratification process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IAM will recommend to our members that they vote `yes' on  
ratification of these revised proposals, which represent a 
significant improvement over previous contract offers from TWA,'' 
union official William O'Driscoll said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA chief executive Bill Compton said employees ``recognizes  
that our employees need the largest raise we can profitably provide 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the new pact will be released Tuesday in Kansas City,  
where the union is based. Workers will begin voting on it on 
Wednesday. The airline is based in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA has survived two trips to bankruptcy court in the 1990s,  
largely because union members have given up salary and other 
benefits to keep the company afloat. The losses have been reduced 
in recent years, but the company has continued to lose money. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Compton warned that TWA ``simply does not have the  
resources to afford a strike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On May 28, TWA presented what it described as its ``last, best  
offer,'' and the rank-and-file had been voting on it even though it 
did not have the approval of union leaders. That deal would have 
brought TWA employees to about 90 percent of the airline industry 
standard by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The new deal nullifies the previous bid and those earlier votes.  
</P>
<P>
	Compton said the sides continued to talk after the voting had  
begun on the last offer. Meetings on the new proposal began in 
earnest last Tuesday and negotiators worked virtually non-stop 
until Sunday morning, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always had an interest in coming up with a package that  
would be endorsed by the Machinists,'' he said. ``It is always 
better to get a deal that is endorsed by both sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's previous offer received little support. Union  
members had also cast ballots on whether to approve limited strikes 
targeting key flights during the Fourth of July weekend, typically 
one of the year's busiest weekends for airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Many union employees had expressed anger at the airline over the  
last proposal, saying they were getting nothing back after years of 
sacrificing wages. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Driscoll said he thought that rancor would dissipate after the  
employees see the latest contract proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers affected by the new offer include flight attendants,  
mechanics, ramp workers and passenger service personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees at the airline's domestic hub at Lambert Airport in  
St. Louis welcomed news of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The airline couldn't afford a strike, and neither could the  
members of the union,'' said Ted Evans, a skycap at Lambert for 24 
years. ``I'm very glad they've got it resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TWA suffered last year when baggage handlers, mechanics and ramp  
workers briefly walked off the job, effectively shutting down the 
airline's hub at Lambert Airport in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is seeking payback for years of what the airline  
acknowledges were subpar wages and cuts in benefits and retirement 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA hasn't turned a profit in 10 years. In 1998, the airline  
lost almost $5 per paying passenger for every 1,000 miles. Since 
1989, TWA has lost more than $2 billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 14:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dallas Stars coach Ken Hitchcock admits  
he's lost control of the locker room. Don't alert the news media -- 
it isn't as bad as it sounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock doesn't say he lost control of his team, he's just  
letting the veterans pass along his message rather than stand up 
and talk to 20 or so players himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you talk to a group of 20 players, there's no impact,''  
Hitchcock said. ``You have to have leaders and let them push the 
message across. If I think there's a problem, I (bring) the 
veterans in and say, `Here's the problem, go solve it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock says it's all part of coaching in the '90s. Hitchcock  
calls himself an ``old-school'' coach who is trying to live with 
the new times. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has become less of Xs and Os, and more of a people  
business,'' Hitchcock said about his relationship with his players. 
``I'm still running drills. Players want a similar routine. (But) 
I'm adapting to compromise.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAR-CROSSSED:* Miroslav Satan was a 40-goal scorer for the  
Sabres during the season, but has practically disappeared in the 
playoffs with only three goals in nine games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars have been particularly tough on the Sabres' top  
goal-scorer in the finals, holding him to no goals and only one 
assist. Asked if he felt any pressure, Satan said, ``Yes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``I tried to respond (Saturday night) the best way I  
can, but right now (the Stars are) backchecking hard. There is not 
too much room; not only me, but the whole team has problems 
creating in their zone. I think that is the key why we only had 12 
shots last night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff is perplexed about Satan's playoff  
performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought added ice time might get him going,'' Ruff said.  
``We tried to get him away from a couple of their matchups; tried 
to get him away from a couple of their defensive pairs. We tried 
everything, but we didn't get a lot out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ONE-TEAM MAN: *Does Ken Hitchcock want to coach another team  
other than the Dallas Stars? Not likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal is to be a one-team coach,'' Hitchcock said. ``I have  
no interest in moving my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock is in his fourth season with the Dallas Stars after  
being hired in the middle of the 1995-96 season. Hitchcock coached 
in Canadian juniors for six years and coach two teams in three 
years in the IHL before joining the Stars. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MATTER OF PERSPECTIVE:* Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff wasn't worried  
that his team was down 2-1 in the best-of-7 Stanley Cup finals with 
Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it was the best-of-3, I'd be really scared right now,''  
Ruff quipped. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO MORE MR. NICE GUY:* Mike Modano had three penalties in the  
second period in Dallas' 2-1 victory over Buffalo on Saturday 
night: tripping, slashing and interference. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's Modano, he was gooning it up pretty good,'' Dallas  
coach Ken Hitchcock said, getting a chuckle from the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Modano is the Stars' all-around best player and known more for  
his scoring than his physical play. 
</P>
<P>
                           	 *--------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHAT A GUY!:* One Dallas player who impresses Buffalo's Mike  
Peca is impressed with is 39-year-old Guy Carbonneau. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a guy that still has a tremendous amount of energy and  
applies it each and every shift. I think the younger guys are 
always learning from stuff like that, when you get a guy that is 39 
who is still working and doing all the little things.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NOT JUST ANOTHER JOE:* Joe Nieuwendyk has established himself  
as a star of the first order with Dallas in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	His 11 goals are tops and his game-winner in Saturday's 2-1  
victory over Buffalo was his sixth, tying an NHL record set by 
Colorado's Joe Sakic in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk said his success started early with the Calgary  
Flames. As a 22-year-old, he was part of a Stanley Cup-winning team 
in 1989 and learned good work habits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was very fortunate to be on a strong Calgary team,''  
Nieuwendyk said. ``I was taught the value of hard work, of what it 
takes to get to the finals at this level.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SITTING PRETTY:* How pivotal was it for the Dallas Stars to win  
Game 3 on Saturday night and take a 2-1 lead in the finals? 
</P>
<P>
	Only this: Teams that have won the third game of a best-of-7  
series that is tied 1-1 have won the Stanley Cup 17 of 20 times. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE LAST WORD:* Brett Hull is a doubtful starter for Tuesday  
night's Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals because of a groin injury, 
and Stars coach Ken Hitchcock was asked if he would possibly be 
behind the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	Absolutely not, said Hitchcock.  
</P>
<P>
	``If Hull's not playing, he's not coming on the bench,''  
Hitchcock said. ``Enough is enough, as far as his opinions are 
concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hull is one of the NHL's most opinionated players and is shy  
about sharing his views. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
