<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *John O. Jarstad    	
</P>
<P>
	BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) -- John O. Jarstad, a former sports  
announcer, journalist and Tacoma city councilman, died Saturday of 
heart failure and diabetes. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1940s, Jarstad was sports editor of the Bremerton Sun and  
the radio voice of the Bremerton Bluejackets, a minor-league 
baseball team. He later broadcast baseball on TV for the Seattle 
Rainiers of the Pacific Coast League, and he hosted an outdoors 
show on Seattle's KOMO-TV for 13 years in the 1950s and '60s. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarstad served on the Tacoma City Council in the late 1960s and  
early 1970s, served a term as the city's deputy mayor and made an 
unsuccessful bid for Congress in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarstad is survived by his wife, Barbara, his son, three  
daughters, a brother and two sisters. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jabu Nkosi    	
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Jabu Nkosi, a jazz keyboardist  
who played with such luminaries as Miriam Makeba and Harry 
Belafonte, has died of heart failure. He was 46. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday Times said Nkosi had high blood pressure, diabetes  
and cirrhosis of the liver. It did not say when he died. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of legendary alto sax and clarinet player Zakes Nkosi,  
Jabu Nkosi left school at an early age and began performing jazz 
with friends and family. 
</P>
<P>
	He never learned to read music but amazed fellow musicians with  
his intuitive grasp of harmony and other concepts. Nkosi's keyboard 
style was characterized by his delicacy and ability to improvise. 
</P>
<P>
	Nkosi was frequently hospitalized the last two years, which  
limited his performances and his financial resources. He lived in 
the black township of Alexandra near Johannesburg, unable to afford 
electricity. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Carmen Perry    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Carmen Perry, whose translation of a Mexican  
officer's memoir ignited controversy because it described the 
supposed capture and execution of Davy Crockett at the Alamo, died 
Friday. She was 93. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly a quarter-century after its publication, ``With Santa  
Anna in Texas: Diary of Jose Enrique de la Pena'' remains the 
subject of debate among historians. 
</P>
<P>
	De la Pena, a lieutenant colonel who served under Mexican Gen.  
Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna, described how Crockett and six other 
Alamo defenders were captured alive after the March 1836 battle. 
The account says that on Santa Anna's orders, Crockett and the 
others were stabbed with bayonets and shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditional accounts have the Alamo volunteers fighting to the  
end, sometimes in hand-to-hand combat. Legend holds that Crockett 
wielded his long-rifle, Betsy, like a club before he fell near the 
front doors of the Alamo's chapel. 
</P>
<P>
	After her translation of the diary was published in 1975, Ms.  
Perry received threatening mail and phone calls from people who 
questioned why she was dishonoring the Texas hero. 
</P>
<P>
	Born on July 4, 1905, in Torreon, Mexico, to a Spanish mother  
and German father, Ms. Perry and her two brothers were taught to 
speak German, English, Spanish and Catalan, a dialect of French and 
Spanish spoken in Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Perrys fled Mexico at the outbreak of the Mexican Revolution  
and settled in San Antonio. Ms. Perry obtained a master's degree in 
Spanish literature from the University of Texas and became a 
leading translator and researcher at the Daughters of the Republic 
of Texas Library at the Alamo from 1959 to 1968. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
