<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: LA Kings Name Murray Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Andy Murray, an assistant coach for  
three NHL teams, will be the new coach of the Los Angeles Kings, 
the Press-Telegram of Long Beach reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray was attending a coaching clinic in Calgary and could not  
be reached for comment. He, his wife Ruth and their three children 
were expected to come to Los Angeles for a news conference 
scheduled for Monday, an NHL source told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Kings spokesman Mike Altieri refused to comment Sunday, except  
to say the team will announce its new head coach at a noon news 
conference Monday near the site of the unfinished Staples Center, 
which will house the Kings and NBA's Lakers and Clippers beginning 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings fired Larry Robinson in April, just days after the  
team missed the playoffs for the third time in his four years as 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	The 48-year-old Murray served on the coaching staffs of three  
NHL teams -- as an assistant with the Philadelphia Flyers in 
1988-1990; the Minnesota North Stars in 1990-91, when they reached 
the Stanley Cup final; and as associate coach of the Winnipeg Jets 
in 1992-1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hired as coach of Canada's national team in 1996 and the  
squad had a 77-29-14 record in his two seasons. The team won a gold 
medal at the World Championships in 1997 before Murray left in May 
1998 to spend more time with his family. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past year, Murray has been the hockey coach at  
Shattuck-St. Mary's, a prep school in Faribault, Minn., about 25 
miles south of Minneapolis. Under Murray, the school went 70-9-2 
and won the Midget Triple A USA Hockey national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sumner, Shattuck-St. Mary's athletics director, said he  
knew Murray was offered the job but didn't know whether he 
accepted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
