<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goodyear, Sumitomo Finalize Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. completed an alliance with Japan's  
Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd. on Sunday, returning the Akron, 
Ohio company as the world's top tire maker for the first time in 
more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear will pay $936 million to Sumitomo, acquire 10 percent  
of the manufacturer and help form six joint ventures around the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
	Sumitomo, which has rights to the Dunlop tire brand in major  
world markets, will get a 1.4 percent stake in Goodyear in a stock 
swap valued at $88 million earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance is expected to save $300 million to $360 million  
during the next three years, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keith Price, a spokesman for Goodyear, said it is too early to  
speculate about whether there will be job cuts, but ``anything 
major is not likely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For consumers, the alliance will mean the Dunlop brand will be  
available in more places, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was announced in February, but final agreements were  
signed Sunday in Tokyo. Joint ventures will begin in September, the 
companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance makes Goodyear a $15 billion player in the $70  
billion tire industry. More consolidation in the industry is 
expected as rivals try to protect their profits amid extra capacity 
and cheap imports from Asia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	``With SRI's strength in Japan and Europe, and Goodyear's  
reputation in North America and Europe, the alliance will be a 
formidable player in the world tire industry,'' said Sumitomo 
Chairman Naoto Saito. 
</P>
<P>
	Samir Gibara, Goodyear chairman and chief executive officer,  
said the alliance will help the companies compete and provide 
benefits to employees, customers, shareholders and suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Bridgestone Corp. and France's Michelin SA have  
dominated the tire industry for nearly a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear has been the world's third-largest automobile tire  
maker, with about 17 percent of the global tire industry. The deal 
gives it about 22 percent of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Sumitomo, based in Kobe, Japan, is Japan's third-largest tire  
company. It has annual sales of about $4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear earned $682 million on $12.6 billion in sales last  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately from Sunday's deal, Goodyear said it is cutting 4,200  
jobs worldwide, or about 4 percent of its 97,000-member work force, 
to save $150 million in expenses annually. Cuts were announced in 
Gadsden, Ala., Freeport, Ill., Europe, Latin America and Goodyear's 
chemical, engineered products and Asia tire divisions. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
