<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Activist To Release Memoir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the pantheon of Vietnam War activists,  
Daniel Ellsberg stands apart. 
</P>
<P>
	Hailed as a hero by many, denounced as a traitor by an American  
president, he survived political and legal assaults to become a 
symbol of one person's ability to change history. 
</P>
<P>
	A 47-volume Defense Department study of the U.S. role in  
Indochina over three decades was classified top secret when 
Ellsberg, a Defense Department analyst, decided to copy it and give 
it to The New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times and the Washington Post published the study as ``The  
Pentagon Papers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, almost 30 years later, Ellsberg is excavating his past from  
boxes of documents that form the basis for his memoir. And he's 
sorting out what was accomplished by his actions, which could have 
been punished by 115 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Did his release of the Pentagon Papers help end the Vietnam War?  
No one is certain, least of all Ellsberg. More than likely, he 
says, it stopped the war from escalating. 
</P>
<P>
	He is convinced that President Nixon would have expanded the war  
had he not feared Ellsberg would disclose even more information. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without Nixon's obsession with me, he would have stayed in  
office,'' Ellsberg said in an interview. ``And had he not been 
removed from office, he would have continued the bombing (in 
Vietnam).'' 
</P>
<P>
	But those who were part of the episode that resulted in  
Ellsberg's federal trial for espionage and conspiracy view his 
legacy in broader terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Dan did goes far beyond the war,'' said Leonard  
Weinglass, an attorney who was part of Ellsberg's defense team. 
</P>
<P>
	``What he represents is someone who broke ranks with the policy  
priesthood and was willing to risk the betrayal label for the sake 
of revealing a policy that had gone awry,'' he said. ``Where are 
the people today who would break ranks and reveal such a policy?'' 
</P>
<P>
	ACLU lawyer Mark Rosenbaum, who as a 24-year-old law student  
took a leave from Harvard University to work on Ellsberg's behalf, 
sees him as the ultimate whistle-blower. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what Dan did was to open up for the country the  
recognition that government did not tell the truth,'' Rosenbaum 
said. ``It was a coming-of-age moment for the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsberg remains wiry and energetic at 68. His hair is silver,  
his eyes still flashing blue. And three decades after he risked 
everything to stop the war, the ghosts of Vietnam, Nixon and the 
advisers Nixon delegated to silence him still linger. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated in the front window of a Washington restaurant, he points  
to a place across the street and says, ``That's where I met with 
John Ehrlichman last year. We had lunch and talked for about six 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got on very well,'' he adds.  
</P>
<P>
	The hunter and the hunted making peace.  
</P>
<P>
	Ehrlichman, Nixon's top domestic adviser, went to prison for his  
role in the 1971 break-in at the office of Dr. Lewis Fielding, a 
psychiatrist who had treated Ellsberg. Ellsberg believes Nixon 
assigned Ehrlichman to ``neutralize'' him. 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon ``had been quoted as using words like traitor about me.  
But I'd always heard he had changed,'' Ellsberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was surprised when Ehrlichman called.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was doing a documentary based on his story, and he felt it  
was very important to include me,'' he said. ``He wanted to get me 
on camera, but that never happened.'' Ehrlichman died Feb. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fielding break-in led to dismissal of charges against  
Ellsberg on grounds of outrageous government misconduct. It led to 
revelations, too, about the Watergate scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Nixon, who resigned in 1974 over Watergate, wrote in his  
memoirs: ``I still believe that it is a tragedy of circumstances 
that ... John Ehrlichman went to jail and Daniel Ellsberg went 
free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Why was Nixon so intent on getting Ellsberg? The former Pentagon  
insider thinks he knows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nixon knew from almost the first day I had other documents  
that I had not released, including documents from his own National 
Security Counsel,'' he said. ``He didn't know how much I had. But 
he thought if I released them, it would expose his Vietnam 
strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nixon had a secret plan and I did know what it was,'' Ellsberg  
said. His contention: Nixon planned to continue the war 
indefinitely with U.S. air support for South Vietnamese troops on 
the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon sent Ellsberg to Vietnam, and he returned knowing  
the war was not being won. In 1969 he decided to release the 
Pentagon Papers to the newspapers to show a pattern of deception 
that he believed guided U.S. foreign policy for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, he said, he could have published it on the Internet, a  
lot less cumbersome than making multiple copies of 7,000 pages of 
documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsberg's current cause is preventing nuclear arms  
proliferation. He has been jailed many times in anti-nuclear 
protests the last 20 years and has moved to Washington to further 
his efforts. His wife, Patricia, lives in their home in Northern 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Their son, Michael, 22, is a law student at Brown University,  
where he recently had an opportunity to chide Robert McNamara, an 
architect of the war his father opposed. Speaking to a class last 
month, the former defense secretary acknowledged harboring doubts 
the United States could win the war. 
</P>
<P>
	``Had you spoken frankly,'' Michael Ellsberg told McNamara, ``it  
seems years of war could have been avoided.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsberg is writing his memoirs and supports himself with  
lecture fees and research grants on nuclear issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenbaum predicts Ellsberg will be seen as a towering figure.  
</P>
<P>
	``There hasn't been anyone else that took such a lonely and  
principled stand,'' Rosenbaum said. ``He did take on the 
government.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
