<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Matchups in NBA Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A position-by-position look at the matchups in the NBA Finals  
between the San Antonio Spurs and New York Knicks: 
</P>
<P>
 *CENTER:   	
</P>
<P>
	David Robinson vs. Chris Dudley. A complete and utter mismatch  
in every way. Robinson is the superior offensive player, able to go 
strong to the hoop, shoot jumpers and draw fouls, and is a better 
rebounder, shot blocker and help defender. Dudley is a big body 
with six fouls. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Spurs.  
</P>
<P>
 *POWER FORWARD:   	
</P>
<P>
	Tim Duncan vs. Kurt Thomas-Larry Johnson. Another mismatch, even  
more so if Johnson's sprained knee keeps him out of the first few 
games. Duncan is fundamentally sound, a superb low-post scorer, a 
shot-blocker and a better passer and free throw shooter than he was 
last season as a rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Spurs.  
</P>
<P>
 *SMALL FORWARD:   	
</P>
<P>
	Sean Elliott vs. Latrell Sprewell. One of the more intriguing  
matchups, and one the Knicks need to win in order to have any 
chance for a title. Sprewell is an outstanding slasher and scorer 
and one of the best finishers around the basket in the NBA. Elliott 
is a better 3-point shooter. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Knicks.  
</P>
<P>
 *SHOOTING GUARD:   	
</P>
<P>
	Mario Elie vs. Allan Houston. Elie, the brashest player on the  
Spurs, and Houston, one of the quietest Knicks, are a study in 
contrasts. Houston, while inconsistent, is a much better shooter 
and scorer. Elie is the superior defender. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Knicks.  
</P>
<P>
 *POINT GUARD:   	
</P>
<P>
	Avery Johnson vs. Charlie Ward-Chris Childs. The Knicks will use  
Ward as their starter and Childs as their finisher, sometimes 
playing the two alongside each other in a three-guard alignment. 
Ward has been playing poorly of late, while Johnson has 
consistently made teams pay for leaving him open. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Spurs.  
</P>
<P>
 *RESERVES:   	
</P>
<P>
	Jaren Jackson, Steve Kerr, Jerome Kersey, Malik Rose and Will  
Perdue vs. Childs, Marcus Camby, Herb Williams and Thomas (if 
Johnson is healthy). Camby is the best player on either bench, 
capable of infusing the Knicks with energy, speed and athleticism. 
In Rose, Kersey and Perdue, the Spurs have lots more height than 
the Knicks. San Antonio also has the edge in 3-point shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Spurs.  
</P>
<P>
 *COACHES:   	
</P>
<P>
	Gregg Popovich vs. Jeff Van Gundy. No one gave Popovich much  
credit for the Spurs' success this season, as evidenced by his 
sixth place showing in coach of the year balloting. Van Gundy has 
been brilliant in the postseason after being stubborn in the 
regular season and nearly losing his job. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Knicks.  
</P>
<P>
 *INTANGIBLES:   	
</P>
<P>
	Low exposure vs. bright spotlight. The pressure of the NBA  
Finals is a whole lot different than anything that comes before it, 
and certain Western Conference marquee players have been known to 
experience brain lock under that pressure in recent years. The 
Knicks shouldn't have a problem with the extra attention, given 
that they play in the unrelenting glare of the nation's No. 1 media 
market and have survived a soap opera season with endless injuries, 
controversies and distractions. 
</P>
<P>
	Advantage -- Knicks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arum Offers Suggestions for Boxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANASTOTA, N.Y. (AP) -- Promoter Bob Arum took his place Sunday  
among the ring's legends in the International Boxing Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Someday, he told thousands of well-wishers, he hopes to  
accomplish something to deserve his place there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes people get an award and then what they do  
subsequently justifies the award. ... I hope that will be the case 
in my situation,'' Arum said during a 10th anniversary induction 
ceremony attended by nearly three dozen past and present champions, 
including Sugar Ray Leonard, Joe Frazier, Floyd Patterson and Leon 
and Michael Spinks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe some day I will really be worthy of this honor you have  
given me today,'' said Arum, who entered the hall along with five 
other living inductees: heavyweight Jimmy Bivins, featherweight 
champion Eusebio Pedroza of Panama, bantam great Khaosai Galaxy of 
Thailand, publicist Irving Rudd and celebrated English manager 
Mickey Duff. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking blame for some of the problems that have beset boxing  
during the last generation, Arum threw out a challenge to himself 
and other fight fans to help boxing ``reestablish itself as the 
major sport it truly is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On a day where levity had been the prevailing tone among the  
earlier recipients, Arum turned serious at the end of the ceremony 
to offer three suggestions to improve boxing. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the continued exploitation of fighters by managers and  
promoters a problem that has soured boxing's public image, Arum 
urged his listeners to help lobby Congress for approval of the 
so-called Muhammad Ali bill, a proposal by Arizona Sen. John 
McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's legislation would require promoters and organizers of  
major boxing events to disclose more financial information and to 
inform state boxing commissions of charges, costs and fees they 
take out of a boxer's purse. The proposal has passed in the Senate 
but has not been taken up by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Arum also said boxing needs one principal body, some type of  
private commission, to run the sport and pilot it through the 
Internet Age if it is to compete globally with other sports. 
Antitrust regulations would require Congressional approval for such 
a body, but the boxing industry itself must finance it, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lastly, and to the cheers of all the boxers, Arum said boxing  
needs to develop a pension fund like other major sports have. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boxing must take care of its own. The past fighters. The  
current fighters. And the future fighters. We don't want the 
fighters to go the community to help. We in boxing must create a 
fund to help those fighters,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arum has been one of boxing's most prominent promoters since  
1966, when he promoted the first fight he ever attended, Muhammad 
Ali vs. George Chuvalo. In 1980, he began the Top Rank Boxing 
series, which became one of ESPN's highest rated regular shows. 
Among the matchups he has brought to the ring were Arguello-Pryor, 
Leonard-Hagler, Hagler-Hearns and Ali-Spinks II. 
</P>
<P>
	While Arum's words brought applause, the biggest ovation Sunday  
was for Bivins, a longtime contender who defeated eight future 
champions but never got a shot at a title fight during a 15-year 
career. Last year, a penniless Bivins was rescued by police and 
family after being found in the attic of his son-in-law's home, 
malnourished, abused and near death. 
</P>
<P>
	At age 79 and fully recovered, Bivins strode slowly to the  
podium as he received a minute-long standing ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank you for cheering like that for me,'' Bivins said softly  
when the applause had quieted. His words ignited another round of 
applause. ``I never figured I'd get a chance to be in front of a 
people like this. ... Everybody talked about I was a bum. But this 
bum came to be somebody.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0102 </DOCNO>
