<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerospace Cos Assume Big Competitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LE BOURGET, France (AP) -- From rockets built in China to  
passenger jets made in Brazil, a growing number of smaller 
aerospace companies are carving successful niches and even 
competing head-on with industry heavyweights like Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	A few have chosen to go it alone, like China Great Wall Industry  
Corp., producer of ``Long March'' rockets used to send commercial 
satellites into orbit. 
</P>
<P>
	Others prefer forming joint projects with bigger, richer  
companies as a way of sharing costs, technologies and the risk of 
failure in one of the world's most capital-intensive businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone trying to launch new projects is looking for  
partners,'' said Robin Ho, project manager for Taiwan's Aerospace 
Industrial Development Corp. ``That's the concept in the aviation 
industry now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ho spoke at the Paris Air Show, which opened to the public on  
Sunday. The show is the biggest event of its kind in the aerospace 
industry -- an eight-day sales promotion for makers of commercial 
and military aircraft and equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,800 companies are participating this year at Le  
Bourget airfield north of the French capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents and young children thronged the show Sunday, packing the  
aisles in indoor exhibit halls and scanning the sky for flight 
demonstrations by cutting-edge jets like the Eurofighter. A 
vintage, World War II-era P-51 Mustang also made a rare, aerobatic 
display. 
</P>
<P>
	For Indonesian Aerospace Industries, the show was an opportunity  
to promote its twin-engine military transport, the CN-235. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, known by its Indonesian acronym IPTN, teamed up  
with CASA of Spain to build the plane. Now it hopes to develop a 
130-seat passenger jet, a step that would put it into direct 
competition with Boeing and Airbus Industrie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see how we can compete with Boeing or Airbus in  
America or Europe,'' said sales and marketing executive Agung B. 
Ismadi. But IPTN is targeting business in Southeast Asia, where 
Ismadi said he sees ``a very big opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The near-collapse of Indonesia's economy has forced IPTN to  
delay development of commercial planes until it can find another 
wealthy partner to share the development costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel Aircraft Industries International has followed a similar  
strategy, linking up with bigger firms like TRW and Raytheon to 
develop new projects. 
</P>
<P>
	``The secret to winning today is giving local companies some  
participation to help offset the cost,'' said IAI International 
vice president Marvin Klemow. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1954 with just seven employees, the Israeli  
government-owned firm has grown into a conglomerate with a work 
force of 13,000 and annual sales of more than $2 billion, Klemow 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's competing head-on with Boeing to sell early-warning  
aircraft to Australia. It hopes to sell 174 attack helicopters to 
Turkey, where its competitors include Italy's Agusta. 
</P>
<P>
	IAI is happy to cut deals to improve its odds. Even if Agusta  
wins the Turkish sale, IAI has agreed to provide night-targeting 
equipment for use with the Italian helicopters, Klemow said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's Embraer is another niche producer with eyes on a larger  
market. The company's president, Mauricio Botelho, said Saturday 
that he has been negotiating with several potential partners in 
hopes of expanding its role as a builder of regional passenger 
planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week it announced the sale of 100-seat commercial jets to  
the Swiss airline Crossair, showing that it wants to grow at the 
expense of established companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Denel, a South African arms manufacturer, also is looking for a  
foreign partner to improve its access to capital and advanced 
technologies, said Willie Pienaar, the company's regional manager 
for Europe. Like IPTN of Indonesia, Denel has built its business in 
specializing in supplying regional markets, like Africa and Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The China Great Wall Industry Corp. has bucked the trend toward  
joint ventures, building its own rockets to carry satellites for 
foreign customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Its main target for business is Asia, where its relatively cheap  
price for launching satellites gives it a competitive edge, said 
Wei Zeng, a company planning assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing, which has its own rocket program, acknowledges the  
threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know it's a commodity business,'' said Jim Albaugh,  
president of Boeing's Space and Communications Group. ``And we're 
going to have to keep moving that price point down.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 13:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murdoch May Buy Publishing Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. reportedly is in  
discussions to acquire the publishing companies William Morrow &AMP; 
Co. and Avon Books. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies, owned by Hearst Corp., would be added to  
Murdoch's HarperCollins group if the deal is concluded, the 
Hollywood Reporter said, quoting unidentified sources who described 
the talks as ``advanced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marcia Horowitz, a Murdoch spokeswoman, had no comment Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Telephone messages seeking comment were left at the New York  
City offices of William Morrow and Avon, which were closed over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based News Corp. reportedly has held talks with several  
mid-sized players in its effort to expand its trade book publishing 
presence. The company had been talking with Viacom Inc. about 
merging HarperCollins with Viacom's Simon &AMP; Schuster, but those 
discussion broke off, the Reporter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several big publishers have merged in recent years, as companies  
seek to cut costs and gain market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the German media conglomerate Bertelsmann bought the  
biggest U.S. book publisher, Random House, from Advance 
Publications, for a price estimated by analysts at between $1.1 
billion and $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of authors raised objections to the merger, saying it  
would create a ``new economic behemoth'' with the potential to 
restrict readers' choices and authors' ability to market their 
works. Nonetheless, the Federal Trade Commission authorized the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Bertelsmann also bought Bantam Books in 1977 and owns Doubleday,  
Dell-Delacorte and Broadway Books. 
</P>
<P>
	Also last year, Viacom Inc. sold the educational, professional  
and reference divisions of Simon &AMP; Schuster to the British media 
group Pearson for $4.6 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
