<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nethercutt Seeking Fourth Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- George Nethercutt, whose pledge to serve  
only three terms in the U.S. House help him upset Speaker Tom Foley 
in 1994, announced Sunday he had changed his mind and would seek a 
fourth two-year term in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made a mistake when I chose to set a limit on my service,''  
Nethercutt, R-Wash., said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	An official for U.S. Term Limits said the group would spend  
close to $1 million in an effort to defeat Nethercutt. 
</P>
<P>
	Nethercutt made term limits the central theme of his 1994  
campaign against Foley, whom he cast as a career politician, and 
won an upset victory during that year's Republican takeover of 
Congress. Foley served in the U.S. House for 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory gave Nethercutt instant standing in the new  
Republican majority and he was rewarded with a seat on the House 
Appropriations Committee -- a rarity for a freshman. 
</P>
<P>
	He won re-election twice while promising to keep his pledge to  
serve only three terms. 
</P>
<P>
	But beginning in 1997, the former attorney said he might run for  
a fourth term if he were convinced it would be good for his 
district. This year, he has said repeatedly in speeches that he 
considers term limits a mistake and that he wished he had never 
made the promise. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Saying the vice president was a strong  
advocate for urban America, more than 100 mayors announced their 
support Sunday for Al Gore's 2000 campaign for president. 
</P>
<P>
	``We represent every region of the United States and we are here  
to make sure Al Gore becomes the next president of the United 
States,'' said New Orleans Mayor Marc Morial, speaking at a news 
conference at the U.S. Conference of Mayors annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining him were dozens of other city leaders, including mayors  
Clarence Harmon of St. Louis, Sharon Sayles Belton of Minneapolis, 
Bill Campbell of Atlanta and Scott King of Gary, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 167 mayors have pledged their support to the Democrat for  
next year's election. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore was scheduled to attend at $1,000 per-person fund-raiser  
here Monday before addressing the conference in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Haley Barbour, co-chairman of Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush's presidential exploratory committee, said Sunday 
that Bush, the GOP front-runner, was not taking Vice President 
Gore's candidacy lightly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we have to be very careful the Republicans don't  
underestimate Al Gore. I don't. Not because I know of some great 
strength he has, but it's foolish in politics to underestimate your 
opponent. And we just should not underestimate Albert Gore. I don't 
think George Bush will ...,'' Barbour said on ``Fox News Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NOTTINGHAM, N.H. (AP) -- Just 40 miles from where Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush was serving lobster to the traveling press, former 
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander on Sunday dined on hamburgers and 
hot dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander met with about 100 voters at a cookout in Pawtuckaway  
State Park, just across New Hampshire's border with Maine. Bush was 
visiting his father, former President George Bush, at the family 
home in Kennebunkport, Maine. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander's supporters tried to play it to his advantage, saying  
his low-key event would contrast with Bush's visit to New Hampshire 
on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Gore's campaign chairman said  
Sunday that Gore has fared poorly in polls against Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush and other Republicans because he has not received 
the credit he deserves for the administration's successes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a member of this team that is responsible for all these  
successes. And members of the team don't always get credit,'' said 
Tony Coehlo, appearing on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The chairman of the Republican National  
Committee said one of the party's missions was to ensure Americans 
got to know the ``real Al Gore.''	   ''He said he cleared land in Tennessee with mules and a 
double-bladed ax. He grew up in a luxury hotel right in Washington. 
He's really not Daniel Boone, he's the boy from embassy row,'' Jim 
Nicholson said on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So we are going to point out to people that luxury hotel in  
Washington where he really was raised,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leon Panetta, a former White House chief of  
staff to President Clinton, said Sunday that GOP Gov. George W. 
Bush of Texas might find campaigning for president becomes rougher 
as people get to know him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look, the governor is a decent man; he's committed to public  
service. He has done a pretty good job as governor in Texas. But 
nobody knows what his positions are on national issues,'' Panetta 
said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And that is what is going to be tested over these next few  
months. And when that's tested he's going to be running into a lot 
of land mines within his own party and within the American people 
as well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
