<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coles Resigns From Sydney Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Phil Coles resigned from the Sydney  
2000 Organizing Committee on Monday but retained his seat on the 
IOC, Olympic officials announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The compromise deal was offered by the International Olympic  
Committee executive board in a bid to close the five-month 
controversy swirling around the Australian IOC member. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles -- who was already censured in March for his role in the  
Salt Lake City scandal -- had been under the threat of expulsion 
from the IOC for further alleged ethical misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive board announced that it was maintaining the ``most  
severe warning'' which Coles received in March for accepting lavish 
hospitality from Salt Lake City bid officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The board said Coles would now receive a ``reprimand'' for  
serious negligence and proposed that he be ineligible to serve on 
any IOC commission or working group for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement announced that Coles had resigned from the board  
of the Sydney organizing committee. Sydney organizers have 
repeatedly pushed for Coles to be ousted from the local panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The board said it found no ``sanctionable offense'' in the fact  
that Coles had written memos on IOC members. Those memos, prepared 
for the Sydney bid committee, were apparently passed on to Salt 
Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the other hand, by not taking all necessary precautions to  
avoid the disclosure of such notes, Mr. Coles was guilty of serious 
negligence,'' an IOC statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sydney, Coles charged that ``political pressures'' had forced  
him off the SOCOG board but said he was relieved he will keep his 
IOC position. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's another disappointing day for me,'' Coles said. ``Still,  
being on the IOC is nice and I appreciate that but it's a sad day 
that political pressures have forced this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles said he believed SOCOG president Michael Knight had forced  
his resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I put it on the table to the IOC that I was open for a meeting  
with Michael Knight which obviously wasn't accepted by him so I 
resigned,'' Coles said. ``There was never any suggestion that I 
would resign from the SOCOG board to keep my role with the IOC, 
never.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles temporarily stepped down from the Sydney board in February  
after being implicated in the Salt Lake vote-buying case. He has 
since been stripped of his role in organizing the Olympic torch 
relay in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	But Knight and other Australian Olympic officials have demanded  
that Coles leave for good, claiming the scandal was detracting from 
the games and scaring away sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Olympic rules, Coles has an automatic seat on the Sydney  
board as one of two IOC members from Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coles case has overshadowed other issues as the IOC meets in  
Seoul for a three-day executive board meeting, followed by a 
four-day session of the general assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	The centerpiece of the session is Saturday's selection of the  
host city for the 2006 Winter Games. Six European cities are in the 
running. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the IOC meetings began, Coles expressed confidence he  
would be cleared. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles told The Sun-Herald newspaper in Sydney he expected to  
reclaim his key posts in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll just be glad when all this business is finally put to  
rest,'' he said. ``I'll have more to say when my name is finally 
cleared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coles reiterated his contention that he was the victim of a  
political vendetta in Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe my name has been turned into a political football  
and I'm talking of people in high places on both sides of state 
politics,'' Coles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has been questioned three times by IOC investigators for  
alleged abuse of his office. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, he received a ``most severe'' warning from the IOC for  
accepting lavish travel and other incentives during Salt Lake's 
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. Six members were expelled 
and four resigned in the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles' case was left open amid further accusations of ethical  
violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC later examined claims by Coles' ex-wife that the couple  
received jewelry valued at $6,000 from a businessman associated 
with the Athens bid for the 1996 Games. No action was taken. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest investigation centers on accusations that Coles, and  
his partner Patricia Rosenbrock, had compiled secret dossiers on 
IOC members for Sydney's successful 2000 bid and passed them on to 
Salt Lake bidders. 
</P>
<P>
	Pal Schmitt, an IOC vice president, has accused Coles of  
breaking ``unwritten ethical rules'' and acting ``against the 
dignity, the pride of IOC members.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Dick Pound, another IOC vice president and a personal friend  
of Coles, dismissed the dossiers as ``normal chitchat'' among bid 
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's done all the time,'' Pound said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 14:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: FAA Probes Emery Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Federal aviation regulators reportedly are  
investigating allegations that Emery Worldwide improperly shipped 
hazardous materials, failed to notify pilots of hazardous cargo and 
concealed problems from inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration began a nationwide  
investigation more than a month ago into the alleged violations, 
Bill Wilkening, manager of the FAA's Dangerous Goods/Cargo Security 
Division in Washington, D.C., told the Dayton Daily News for 
Sunday's edition. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephones at the division's offices rang unanswered over the  
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Emery Worldwide spokesman Rocco Sacci told the newspaper that  
Emery Worldwide and Emery Worldwide Airlines cannot respond 
directly to any current or pending government agency investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement to the newspaper, he said, ``The two  
companies have spent hundreds of thousands of dollars and thousands 
of hours in development and training to achieve what we believe to 
be the finest program for the handling of hazmat shipments that can 
be found in the air industry. Our service centers are very 
sensitive to the training, acceptance and proper handling of all 
shipments that fall into the dangerous goods category.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sacci said the companies have not been told of any violations  
regarding hazardous material handling or other operational issues 
other than minor administrative errors. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledged that FAA inspectors have been auditing Emery  
Worldwide's operations. Sacci would not elaborate Sunday when 
reached by The Associated Press at his home. 
</P>
<P>
	The FAA probe is focused on Emery's North American freight hub  
at Dayton International Airport through which much of the company's 
cargo -- including hazardous materials -- flows, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News said it obtained copies of documents made  
available to the FAA showing that Debbra O. Bullock, a hazardous 
materials supervisor at Emery's Dayton hub, repeatedly brought 
complaints of violations to her superiors, but she said little was 
done. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bullock, 40, told the newspaper she has been interviewed  
extensively by the FAA. She continues to work at Emery in another 
supervisory job. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bullock has an unpublished telephone number and could not be  
reached for additional comment Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines are permitted to carry hazardous materials, but the  
shipments are subject to strict federal regulations and require 
special labeling, documentation, handling and loading. 
</P>
<P>
	Emery Worldwide operates one of the biggest U.S. airlines  
specializing in freight, serving customers from small retail 
shippers to auto companies and the Department of Defense. Based in 
Redwood City, Calif., Emery Worldwide has more than 75 cargo 
aircraft, 2,000 trucks and vans, and 560 service centers in 229 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	A unit of CNF Transportation Inc., Emery moves more than 4  
million pounds of freight per day through Dayton. Hazardous 
material shipments account for less than 3 percent of Emery 
Worldwide's total annual shipments, Sacci said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  German Troops Under Fire in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRIZREN, Yugoslavia (AP) -- German troops came under heavy sniper  
fire Sunday in this southern Kosovo city and killed at least one 
armed man and wounded another in the firefight. A German soldier 
suffered an arm wound. 
</P>
<P>
	The German peacekeepers had been greeted earlier by cheering  
ethnic Albanians when they entered Prizren, Kosovo's second-largest 
city, in Germany's first major military deployment on foreign soil 
since World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	As they approached the center of the city on a main street along  
the Bistrica River, sniper fire crackled from a hill and houses. 
German soldiers took cover and began shooting back. 
</P>
<P>
	The Germans' heavy fire blasted a yellow Lada car with two  
occupants. One was slumped dead over the steering wheel and the 
other was badly wounded and screaming for help before he was 
evacuated by German medics. A woman resident was also reported 
wounded by snipers. 
</P>
<P>
	German soldiers said that the men shot first and that grenades  
and semi-automatic weapons were found in the car. 
</P>
<P>
	As reporters hid behind vehicles, German soldiers took up  
defensive positions below the hill from which the sniper fire was 
coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all over the place,'' one soldier said. ``They're  
drunks with guns and grenades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanian teen-agers scrambled about, helping the Germans  
locate sniper positions. One boy told the soldiers he had seen Serb 
snipers hiding in a Roman Catholic Church. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the firefight, arriving German soldiers got a taste  
of Prizren's ethnic tensions. Although initially basking in the 
cheers of a flower-bearing crowd, they quickly had to break up an 
angry confrontation between ethnic Albanians and departing Serb 
militiamen. 
</P>
<P>
	The residents threw stones at some Serb militia vehicles, kicked  
at them and cursed. Serbs aimed their weapons at the Albanians, but 
did not shoot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we may not have everything under control at present,  
we have enough presence in town to believe there will be a safe 
withdrawal'' of Serbs, said Brig. Gen. Fritz von Korff, commander 
of the German-Dutch brigade in Prizren. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the number of troops under his command would double to  
about 2,400 on Monday. But he warned that Prizren was still ``a 
dangerous place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,000 German soldiers with tanks and other armored  
vehicles were expected to be in the city 55 miles southwest of the 
provincial capital, Pristina, by nightfall. The German forces in 
and around Prizren eventually are to number 8,500 -- postwar 
Germany's largest foreign military deployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeping the lid on ethnic tensions and creating safe conditions  
for refugees to return could prove a difficult task for the 
Germans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Prizren area holds some of the Serbian Orthodox Church's  
most cherished sites and some people fear ethnic Albanians might 
vandalize the buildings in retaliation for abuses by Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Church leaders called Sunday for protection of Serb clergy  
remaining in Prizren, the independent Beta news agency reported. It 
said a Serb clergyman was attacked in Ljubizda, a village near 
Prizren. 
</P>
<P>
	As they entered Kosovo from Albania early in the day, the German  
units passed through a heavily vandalized Yugoslav customs post 
where looters had taken nearly everything they could carry -- from 
tables to toilets. 
</P>
<P>
	On the 11-mile road from the border to Prizren, almost no  
residents were seen although the troops passed 200 to 300 Serbian 
soldiers who were withdrawing, many of them appearing downcast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:30:25 </DATE_TIME>
