<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Notes Soft Industry Downturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LE BOURGET, France (AP) -- Airbus Industrie sees a  
softer-than-expected downturn in the aerospace industry and hopes 
to book around 300 orders for its aircraft in 1999, Chairman Noel 
Forgeard said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not as pessimistic as I was earlier,'' Forgeard said at a  
news conference at the Paris Air Show. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest air show, held every two years at Le Bourget  
airport north of Paris, opened to the public Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The air show, expected to draw some 300,000 visitors, is a forum  
for showing off the latest aerospace technology and for sealing and 
announcing lucrative contracts in the multi-billion dollar 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight-day air show opened Saturday to the press on an  
ominous note with the crash of a Russian Sukhoi-30 MK, a fighter 
jet making a demonstration flight. The two pilots safely ejected 
from the flaming aircraft which tumbled to the ground far from the 
crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, it was business as usual.  
</P>
<P>
	Airbus' Forgeard said the European consortium booked 560  
aircraft orders in 1998 with a total value of $39 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Including contracts to be unveiled during the air show, Airbus  
has booked a total of 190 orders since the beginning of this year, 
Forgeard said. Airbus plans to deliver 293 planes this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Airbus Military Co., the defense arm of Airbus  
Industrie, said it expects to receive firm commitments for its 
A400M military transportation aircraft project by early 2000. First 
deliveries are expected by 2006. 
</P>
<P>
	The commitments are expected to come out of discussions with  
seven European governments -- France, Germany, Italy, the U.K., 
Belgium, Spain and Turkey, an AMC statement said. The seven have 
expressed needs for a total of 288 A400M aircraft, to be designed 
to transport a 30-ton payload over a distance of up to 3,230 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The aircraft faces fierce competition from Lockheed Martin Corp.  
The U.S. defense aerospace group is trying to convince European 
governments to opt for its C130J, the latest version of its 
Hercules air transportation aircraft, which is already flying. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments, French aerospace group Dassault Aviation  
plans to split its military and civil businesses by the end of 1999 
to facilitate the integration of its defense unit into future 
European jet fighter programs, Chairman Serge Dassault said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, known for its Mirage and Rafale jet fighters, as  
well as for its Falcon business jets, will create two fully-owned 
units: Dassault Defense and Dassault Falcon, 
</P>
<P>
	Dassault Aviation has no immediate plan to float the new units  
on the stock market, Serge Dassault said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0115 </DOCNO>
