<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TWA, Union Reach Tentative Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Trans World Airlines and its major union  
representing flight attendants, mechanics and other workers reached 
a tentative agreement Sunday on a new contract, possibly averting a 
strike that could have jeopardized the long-struggling company. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Machinists said it would cancel  
the rank-and-file voting that began last week, and then present the 
new contract offer to its members. The union represents 16,000 of 
TWA's 21,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders agreed there would be no work stoppages during the  
monthlong ratification process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IAM will recommend to our members that they vote `yes' on  
ratification of these revised proposals, which represent a 
significant improvement over previous contract offers from TWA,'' 
union official William O'Driscoll said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA chief executive Bill Compton said the company ``recognizes  
that our employees need the largest raise we can profitably provide 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the new pact will be released Tuesday in Kansas City,  
Mo., where the union is based. Workers will begin voting on it on 
Wednesday. The airline is based in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis television stations reported that the new contract is  
for just 18 months rather than the previous 2 1/2-year offer. TWA 
spokesman Jim Brown would not comment on the length of the 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA has survived two trips to bankruptcy court in the 1990s,  
largely because union members have given up salary and other 
benefits to keep the company afloat. The losses have been reduced 
in recent years, but the company has continued to lose money. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Compton warned that TWA ``simply does not have the  
resources to afford a strike.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On May 28, TWA presented what it described as its ``last, best  
offer,'' and the rank-and-file had been voting on it even though it 
did not have the approval of union leaders. That deal would have 
brought TWA employees to about 90 percent of the airline industry 
standard by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The new deal nullifies the previous bid and those earlier votes.  
</P>
<P>
	Compton said the sides continued to talk after the voting had  
begun on the last offer. Meetings on the new proposal began in 
earnest last Tuesday and negotiators worked virtually non-stop 
until Sunday morning, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always had an interest in coming up with a package that  
would be endorsed by the Machinists,'' he said. ``It is always 
better to get a deal that is endorsed by both sides.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's previous offer received little support. Union  
members had also cast ballots on whether to approve limited strikes 
targeting key flights during the Fourth of July weekend, typically 
one of the year's busiest weekends for airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Many union employees had expressed anger at the airline over the  
last proposal, saying they were getting nothing back after years of 
sacrificing wages. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Driscoll said he thought that rancor would dissipate after the  
employees see the latest contract proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers affected by the new offer include flight attendants,  
mechanics, ramp workers and passenger service personnel. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees at the airline's domestic hub at Lambert Airport in  
St. Louis welcomed news of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The airline couldn't afford a strike, and neither could the  
members of the union,'' said Ted Evans, a skycap at Lambert for 24 
years. ``I'm very glad they've got it resolved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TWA suffered last year when baggage handlers, mechanics and ramp  
workers briefly walked off the job, effectively shutting down the 
airline's hub at Lambert Airport in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is seeking payback for years of what the airline  
acknowledges were subpar wages and cuts in benefits and retirement 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	TWA hasn't turned a profit in 10 years. In 1998, the airline  
lost almost $5 per paying passenger for every 1,000 miles. Since 
1989, TWA has lost more than $2 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 11:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cate Blanchett Mulls Perks of Acting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Acting isn't everything for Cate Blanchett, the  
Oscar-nominated star of ``Elizabeth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But having a normal life isn't easy for the movie star who got  
married two years ago, so the best perks accompanying the filming 
of her upcoming movie, ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' in Rome, 
Naples, and Venice were the romantic locales. 
</P>
<P>
	``I finally had a honeymoon with my husband in Italy,''  
Blanchett says in Sunday's Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Australian actress also costars in the upcoming  
film ``An Ideal Husband,'' an adaptation of the Oscar Wilde play of 
the same name. She plays the overly moralistic Lady Gertrude 
Chiltern, a part she chose because of its inherent challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	I thought ``it would be interesting to play a prig who  
unravels,'' Blanchett said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe you have to fall in love with your character.  
It's important to present the unpalatable, flawed side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blanchett's other film credits include ``Pushing Tin,''  
``Paradise Road'' and ``Oscar and Lucinda.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 09:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Department Sending China Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering is  
going to Beijing to discuss NATO's bombing of the Chinese embassy 
in Belgrade and repair faltering U.S.-China relations, Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said Pickering would lead  
a team of administration officials departing Monday for Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit comes as several matters have chilled bilateral  
relations: allegations of Chinese theft of U.S. nuclear secrets; 
stalled talks on China's entry into the World Trade Organization; 
and Congress is debating China's future trade status. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to NATO's errant bombing of the embassy May 7, China  
cut off military contacts, suspended the WTO talks and allowed 
demonstrators to stone the U.S. embassy in Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese officials have demanded a full accounting of the  
incident and wants those responsible punished. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright said Pickering would explain to the Chinese what went  
wrong when a U.S. plane bombed the embassy instead of the intended 
Serbian target several blocks away. She said he would also 
emphasize that ``this was a tragic accident,'' a conclusion the 
Chinese government officially has refused to accept. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickering will carry the message that U.S.-China relations are  
important, ``one that needs to get beyond this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The relations have taken some steps backward as a result of the  
bombing, she said, ``but I believe that we must move forward, as do 
they, in terms of rekindling the WTO talks and other issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China and the United States this spring were within sight of a  
broad market-opening agreement as a prelude to China's entry to the 
WTO. But the talks slowed as a result of the nuclear theft charges, 
which heightened anti-Chinese sentiment in Congress, and then broke 
down after the Belgrade incident. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. negotiators insist that WTO agreement would benefit the  
United States, applying international trade rules to China and 
reducing tariffs that contributed to a $57 billion surplus in 
China's favor last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has begun its annual debate over whether to go along  
with President Clinton's decision to extend normal trade status to 
China for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is expected to abide by that decision, as it has every  
year since 1980, but only after a noisy debate in which critics 
will assail China for its trade practices, human rights record and 
threats to U.S. security. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 13:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain fell across the Midwest on Sunday, while storms also  
stretched across the Southeast. Most of the West was dry. 
</P>
<P>
	A steady rain fell in Wisconsin through northeastern Illinois,  
northwestern Indiana and Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers also fell in Kentucky and Tennessee through Mississippi  
and Alabama. Storms were seen over Florida and along the Gulf 
Coast, into east Texas. Other scattered showers and storms fell in 
Oklahoma and throughout Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered showers developed from New York to northeastern North  
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Clouds were also seen in the Pacific Northwest. The rest of the  
West was dry and clear. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 29 in  
Yellowstone, Wyo., to an early afternoon high of 91 in Phoenix. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 15:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the former  
president who once called himself Mexico's favorite villain, left 
Mexico on Sunday after his first visit in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	In a near-unanimous show of disapproval, Mexicans vented their  
anger against Salinas, who left the country in disgrace in March 
1995, three months after the end of his six-year presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	He is widely blamed for the collapse of the Mexican peso three  
weeks after he left office, sending Mexico into an economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of a public-relations effort, Salinas gave interviews to  
Mexico's two TV networks and offered a press conference, but his 
attempts to defend his image appeared to have failed. 
</P>
<P>
	At the press conference Saturday, he said that a ``tenacious''  
four-year media campaign had been waged against him. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Federal anti-narcotics agents raided 176  
properties -- including luxurious antique-furnished homes -- 
belonging to imprisoned bosses of the Cali drug cartel, authorities 
said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In operations that began last week, agents took control of  
houses, ranches, apartments and offices in 11 cities belonging to 
convicted drug traffickers Gilberto and Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rodriguez brothers were caught by police in 1995 and  
sentenced to 10 and 20 years in jail respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	The properties -- with an estimated value of $14.8 million -- had  
been registered in the name of third parties, said the DAS state 
security agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia enacted sweeping asset forfeiture legislation in 1996  
that allowed authorities to seize properties belonging to convicted 
drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- An armed gang posing as visitors to a  
Brazilian prison overpowered two guards Sunday and allowed 60 of 66 
inmates inside to flee, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gang of four pulled out guns as the guards opened the main  
gates at visiting time, detective Elias Kobachi said by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	Some escapees fled in six cars they stole from where they were  
parked near the prison in Sumare, 110 miles northwest of Sao Paulo, 
she said. Only three inmates were immediately recaptured. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a week ago, in the biggest prison break in Brazil's  
history, 315 inmates fled a prison near Sao Jose dos Campos, in Sao 
Paulo state. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, some 2,200 inmates have escaped from prisons  
and precinct jails in the state. In 1998, the total was 5,888, 
according to police figures. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil is getting ready to offer  
sections of Latin America's largest country for exploration to 
foreign oil companies after the breakup of a 46-year state 
monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the world's biggest oil companies are to bid for 27  
potential oil and gas sites at a massive auction Tuesday and 
Wednesday. Among 37 bidders are Shell, Esso, Texaco and Mobil. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the first auction of its kind since the state-owned  
Petrobras' monopoly was abolished almost four years ago. Petrobras 
will participate at the auction and may form partnerships with 
foreign firms. 
</P>
<P>
	David Zylberstztajn, director of the Brazil's National Oil  
Agency, the industry regulator, predicts that $15 billion to $20 
billion will be invested in Brazil over five years following the 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A leading Venezuelan historian on  
Sunday called for the armed forces to intervene if President Hugo 
Chavez uses a constituent assembly to dissolve Congress and the 
Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, the leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt, has said that  
an assembly to be elected July 25 to rewrite Venezuela's 
constitution should dissolve the other branches of government 
because they are corrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	But historian Jorge Olavarria, who Sunday officially announced  
his candidacy for the election, said that would be the equivalent 
of a coup, in effect giving Chavez dictatorial powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez's leftist Patriotic Pole coalition is expected to  
dominate the assembly. He argues that the assembly will have the 
right to shut down Congress and the courts, which he says would be 
replaced by institutions created by the assembly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
