<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astros Have Suffered Health Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- On the day Astros manager Larry Dierker had a  
seizure and collapsed in the Houston dugout during a game, former 
star pitcher J.R. Richard threw out the ceremonial first pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	How eerie.  
</P>
<P>
	On July 30, 1980, Richard collapsed while working out in the  
Astrodome. Unlike Dierker, who had what physicians called a grand 
mal seizure, an ailment associated with epilepsy, Richard had a 
stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard fell along the first-base line, just a few feet from  
where Dierker collapsed Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgery was required to remove a blood clot in Richard's right  
arm, and the health problem pretty much ended the promising career 
of what was then one of baseball's most dominating pitchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker's difficulty, which forced suspension of Sunday's game  
against San Diego, is the latest in a line of non-baseball health 
problems to involve the Astros. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1962, Jim Umbricht came to the then-Houston Colt .45s and  
became one of the top relief pitchers in the game. Two years later, 
he died of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Wilson pitched two no-hitters for the Astros, set a club  
record with 18 strikeouts in a game in 1968 and made the NL 
All-Star team in 1971. He died in January 1975, asphyxiated in his 
car as it idled in his garage. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, first base coach Jose Cruz left the team May 10 for  
treatment for an irregular heartbeat. Six days later, hitting coach 
Tom McCraw left for treatment of prostate cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Dierker, who said he didn't really believe in ``the curse,''  
suggested that with the hundreds of players to wear the Houston 
uniform, ``some of them were bound to encounter bad luck and bad 
health along the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps Houston has had more than its fair share of  
misfortune,'' he added. ``But I don't think Stephen King will want 
to write a book about it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
