<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tide-Canes Baseball Rivalry in Works </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- A matchup between Alabama and Miami in the  
College World Series is becoming a familiar sight. Hurricanes coach 
Jim Morris said it is developing into a regular rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've played them six times and we're 3-3,'' Morris said  
Saturday. ``We know we're going to have to play hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris said pitching will be the difference when the top-seeded  
Hurricanes (47-13) play the Crimson Tide (52-14) on Sunday. Morris 
is going with right-hander Alex Santos (11-3, 3.10 ERA). 
</P>
<P>
	``Santos doesn't look like the kind of pitcher that gives up the  
kinds of runs that we've been getting,'' Alabama coach Jim Wells 
said. ``He doesn't walk very many people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells will counter with right-hander Manny Torres (10-2, 4.89  
ERA), who battled injuries and arm fatigue over the past two 
seasons. He expects to be challenged by the Hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're an aggressive team,'' Torres said. ``They put the bat  
on the ball. But if I get into the groove early, I think I'll have 
a shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an elimination game, Oklahoma State (46-20) plays Rice  
(58-14). 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama leads the series against Miami 8-5 but the last three  
meetings have all come in Omaha. The Tide has a 16-game winning 
streak after beating Oklahoma State 11-3 on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Santos was scheduled to start for the Hurricanes in the opener  
against Rice, but Morris put in David Gil shortly before the first 
pitch. Miami won 8-4 after trailing 4-0 in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It (the decision) had absolutely nothing to do with Alabama,''  
Morris said. ``I don't think you can look ahead in this tournament. 
If you start looking ahead, you'll be behind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's other game, Oklahoma State coach Tom Holliday will  
start sophomore left-hander Matt Smith (9-5, 2.93 ERA) against the 
Owls. 
</P>
<P>
	``They play the game by the book,'' Holliday said. ``They bunt  
when they're supposed to. They hit and run when they're supposed 
to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys practiced minimally Saturday, holding a makeshift  
batting practice in shorts and T-shirts. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Kenny Baugh (11-2, 2.25 ERA) will start for Rice as  
the Owls try to rebound from a tough loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a little psychologically impaired,'' Rice coach Wayne  
Graham said. ``We told our guys they're a four-game winning streak 
from a national title and they can't give in to any bad breaks.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
