<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 15:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Search for Secrets to Spurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- The archive on ``How To Beat The Spurs''  
is not a voluminous one, which is what Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy 
learned when he started researching his next assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked our video coordinator: `Pull up all their losses. I  
want to see the teams that beat them in the last three months.' And 
he gives me this little stack of tapes,'' Van Gundy said. ``Baaaad 
sign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was looking for a nugget. And what there was,'' he added,  
``were no nuggets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another daunting task awaited them Sunday as the New York Knicks  
had their first practice in preparation for for the NBA Finals, 
which begin Wednesday night at San Antonio's Alamodome. 
</P>
<P>
	How does a New York team missing two frontline starters, Patrick  
Ewing and Larry Johnson, stand a chance of beating a San Antonio 
team with two 7-footers, David Robinson and Tim Duncan, who have 
confounded even the healthiest of teams? 
</P>
<P>
	``Other guys are going to have to -- that old cliche -- step up.  
Do a little more in a lot of different areas. We still have enough 
guys to play,'' Van Gundy said. 
</P>
<P>
	But exactly how many guys they'll have, at least in Game 1,  
remained uncertain. Johnson, who sprained his knee in the clinching 
Game 6 against Indiana, said he plans to play sometime in the 
series even if he can't go in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not good,'' he said of his knee, which was bothering him so  
much at 6 a.m. Sunday that he called trainer Mike Saunders to 
request immediate treatment. ``Not good, But I'm going to be 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to get out there regardless,'' Johnson said.  
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, the Spurs had a day off from practice Sunday as  
the players further enjoyed the downtime they earned by disposing 
of the Portland Trail Blazers in a four-game sweep. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio, which also swept the Los Angeles Lakers in the  
second round, hasn't lost since the second game of the first round 
against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams that are inconsistent, or not as good, you can exploit  
because they have weaknesses,'' Van Gundy said of the Spurs. ``But 
this team really has no weaknesses, which is why they've won 10 
playoff games in a row, which is unheard of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Johnson can't play in Game 1, the Knicks would be expected to  
use a starting lineup of Chris Dudley at center, Kurt Thomas and 
Latrell Sprewell at forward and Allan Houston and Charlie Ward in 
the backcourt. 
</P>
<P>
	That would leave Marcus Camby and 41-year-old Herb Williams as  
the only big men coming off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	That size predicament had Van Gundy and his staff wondering  
whether to double-team Duncan and Robinson when they have the ball, 
as most teams do, or take their chances with single coverage on the 
Twin Towers and tight defense on the other three players. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what's going to be great to watch,'' Van Gundy said.  
``It's going to be a great, great decision for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs, meanwhile, are hoping rest doesn't lead to rust after  
their long layoff. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll also have to overcome the inclination of taking the  
Knicks lightly because of all their injury woes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it hurts them,'' forward Sean Elliott said. ``I think  
in spurts sometimes they're better without Patrick, but I couldn't 
see it for 48 minutes. They've played well, but I think against us 
they need some people who match up inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs and Knicks did not play each other during the regular  
season because of the lockout-shortened schedule, so there will be 
a greater degree of unfamiliarity in this series than there ever 
has been in an NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio swept the two-game season series in 1997-98, but  
those Knicks were nothing like the current squad -- an uptempo, 
athletic mix who were at their best playing like greyhounds against 
the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be tougher in transition against San Antonio  
because those guys run real well,'' said Camby, who provided the 
Knicks with a huge lift of the bench in the Indiana series. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Dudley: ``It definitely will be more difficult without  
Larry. He's been a huge part of our success and he's integral to 
our team, but we'll move forward if he can't play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At practice, Van Gundy showed the players a tape of the final  
seven minutes of Game 6 against Indiana and asked them to savor it 
for the rest of their lives -- but only after they forget about it 
for the next two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a special time, that's going to be a special memory,  
but hopefully there are more special memories to come,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heaping praise on the Spurs, Van Gundy lauded them for  
recovering from their 6-8 start and for winning 42 of their last 48 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``They lost to Phoenix, Dallas, Sacramento in overtime and  
Minnesota. That's it since April 1,'' Van Gundy said. ``That's the 
stack. Four of 'em.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And with that, he headed back to his office, perhaps for another  
crack at deciphering the elusive secrets those four videos hold on 
how to beat the Spurs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990613.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 07:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Want Bats To Perform Like Wood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- An NCAA panel on Saturday recommended that  
equipment manufacturers make college baseball's aluminum bats 
behave as much as possible like wooden bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Milton Gordon, chairman of the NCAA Baseball Research Panel and  
president of Cal State-Fullerton, cited player safety and the 
integrity of the game during a news conference between sessions of 
the College World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wooden bat risk levels should be the safety standard for all  
non-wooden bats,'' Gordon said. ``With regard to the issue of 
balance, the use of non-wooden bats has altered the nature of 
college baseball in recent years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel recommended delaying implementation of the wood-like  
standard until Jan. 1 so additional testing could be performed. The 
rules, if implemented, would be used next season. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's recommendations will be passed to the NCAA Baseball  
Rules Committee and the NCAA Executive Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of several baseball equipment manufacturers sat  
in on the announcement in the Rosenblatt Stadium press room and 
peppered Gordon and other panelists with questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Darby of Easton Sports expressed concern that manufacturers  
wouldn't be able to produce the new bats in time for next season if 
the NCAA keeps pushing back an Aug. 1 deadline for adopting new 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our biggest problem is how long is this going to take,'' Darby  
said. ``We were told last year this was going to be set up by now. 
If it's not ready, how can we make bats for next season?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Darby also objected to the panel's designation of a Baum Hitting  
Machine at the University of Massachusetts as the only device used 
to determine testing on the metal bats. Baum is one of Easton's 
competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel wants college bats to simulate the velocity of a  
batted ball using a ``major league baseball-quality, 34-inch, 
solid-wood bat.'' Darby questioned how the NCAA would determine 
which manufacturer's bat would establish the standard. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also recommended:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Testing speeds for baseballs and bat swings be increased from  
70 mph to 80 mph to better approximate game conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Additional testing to determine if a standard should be  
developed on how tight a regulation NCAA baseball should be wound. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Testing to gather data on the concept of ``work-hardening,''  
or whether a bat begins to perform better the more it is used. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of changes approved last year by the NCAA, many  
college baseball teams played this season with smaller bats that 
performed more like wood than the aluminum bats of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A record 62 home runs were hit in last year's College World  
Series and the tournament ended with Southern Cal's 21-14 victory 
over Arizona State. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, six of the eight coaches in this year's CWS said  
they liked the way the reduced bats had performed this spring. Most 
said they wouldn't like the trend to continue toward wood-like 
bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford coach Mark Marquess, interviewed before the start of  
the Cardinal's game against Cal State-Fullerton, said he doesn't 
support additional changes at a time when record crowds are 
attending the College World Series and the NCAA's expanded 64-team 
bracket sent regionals to new areas of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who are we pleasing?'' Marquess asked. ``I hope we're pleasing  
our fans.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
