<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr To Continue Clinton Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He has been in office through three election  
seasons and is heading into a fourth. So where will Independent 
Counsel Kenneth Starr be in the year 2000? 
</P>
<P>
	He's not sure, Starr says of his nearly five-year investigation,  
declaring he still has work to do. 
</P>
<P>
	The next critical step is the trial of Webster Hubbell for  
allegedly concealing his own and Hillary Rodham Clinton's legal 
work on a fraudulent Arkansas land deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking forward to a trial this summer; that's what  
we're preparing for right now,'' Starr said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The work that Hubbell and Mrs. Clinton did on the 1,050-acre  
project called Castle Grande -- which was owned by Whitewater 
partner Jim McDougal and Hubbell's father-in-law -- was not revealed 
until the first lady's billing records turned up in the White House 
family residence in 1996 under still-unexplained circumstances. 
Prosecutors had been looking for the documents since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Mrs. Clinton's possible Senate bid from New York  
was affecting his office's decision-making, Starr said: ``We strive 
mightily while providing public information, public education, to 
divorce our decisions from politics whatsoever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr declined to give a time frame for completing his job,  
saying ``we recognize that we need to move forward promptly,'' but 
``certain things are not entirely under my control; in fact, some 
things are entirely out of my control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He cited less-than-complete cooperation as prolonging the probe.  
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell and other witnesses have not provided Starr with answers  
to key questions he is investigating, such as the role of Mrs. 
Clinton. Also, the White House has gone to court to challenge Starr 
on many aspects of his investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said he ultimately will file a final report on his  
investigation, as mandated by the independent counsel statute 
expiring this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made no decisions with respect to the specific  
contents of the report,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's TV appearance coincided with publication of excerpts  
from a new book that says in the days before President Clinton was 
questioned in Paula Jones' sexual harassment lawsuit, Clinton's 
lawyer thought his client's ``Achilles' heel'' was not Monica 
Lewinsky but rather an Arkansas woman. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman had met Clinton four times in less than three months  
between his 1992 election and 1993 inauguration. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, by Bob Woodward of The Washington Post, says attorney  
Robert Bennett told Clinton in preparation for his testimony on 
Jan. 17, 1998, that ``your political enemies will eat you alive if 
there's anything in that deposition that isn't truthful. ... You 
are dead. You are dead!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hear you,'' Clinton is said to have replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Woodward's book, ``Shadow: Five Presidents and the Legacy of  
Watergate,'' says that in another conversation concerning the 
testimony, Bennett told Clinton: ``If you're caught ... in the 
White House, I'm not good enough to help you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a prison,'' the president is said to have replied. ``I  
purposefully have no drapes on the windows.'' As for women, ``I'm 
retired, I'm retired,'' he told Bennett, according to the book. 
Clinton was later impeached but survived the attempt to remove him 
from office. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett did not return a telephone call Sunday and the White  
House declined comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
