<HEADLINE> SeaWorld Whale Tries To Bite Trainer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A killer whale tried to bite a trainer during a  
show before hundreds of spectators at SeaWorld, but the trainer 
escaped injury by quickly jumping out of the water. 
</P>
<P>
	The show ended a few minutes earlier than usual Saturday after  
the 5,000-pound whale tried to ``nip'' the trainer, spokesman Bob 
Tucker said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Attack is definitely the wrong word,'' Tucker said. ``The  
trainer turned around and performed in the next show later that 
night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old female whale will be allowed to participate in  
shows, but trainers won't go in the water with her until officials 
determine what may have prompted the whale to try to bite the 
trainer. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're capable of doing tremendous damage,'' SeaWorld  
spokesman Mike Scarpuzzi said. ``But I think in this case, she (the 
whale) just basically said, `I need to communicate something here. 
Something's not right and I need to let you know.''' 
  	   	
</P>
