<HEADLINE> Stanford's Wayne Takes On Fla. St. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Florida State's Matt Diaz and Marshall  
McDougall are the kind of sluggers who might concern opposing 
pitchers. Stanford's Justin Wayne is worried about the Seminoles' 
whole lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne throws for sixth-seeded Stanford (49-13) against the  
second-seeded Seminoles (54-12) on Monday at the College World 
Series. 
</P>
<P>
	In an elimination game, Texas A&AMP;M (52-17) plays Cal  
State-Fullerton (49-13). 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne (9-1, 4.92 ERA) is another in a string of standout  
pitchers from Stanford like Jack McDowell, Mike Mussina and Jeff 
Austin, last year's top draft pick by the Kansas City Royals. 
</P>
<P>
	In his two years, Wayne has a 15-1 record for the best winning  
percentage in school history. The sophomore right-hander from 
Honolulu has 131 strikeouts in 20 starts this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayne said Sunday he's ready for McDougall, who hit six home  
runs in one game last month at Maryland, and Diaz, who hit two in 
Florida State's 7-3 defeat of the Aggies in the CWS opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are some big bats coming at us,'' Wayne said. ``But I  
watched their game against Texas A&AMP;M and it's not just those two. 
It's definitely one through nine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford coach Mark Marquess said it's not smart to focus on any  
hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem with the postseason is you can shut down the  
so-called main guys and someone else can come back and hurt you,'' 
Marquess said. ``Wayne's got all the pitches and has good control. 
We're just going to try to not give up anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Seminoles counter with one of the top pitching staffs in the  
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Starter Jon McDonald (9-2, 3.24), a right-hander, struck out 113  
this season. Reliever Chris Chavez (7-5) struck out six over the 
final five innings of Florida State's win over Texas A&AMP;M. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Seminoles certainly have no monopoly on power hitters.  
Joe Borchard, Josh Hochgesang and Edmund Muth all homered to help 
Stanford beat Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late game, Texas A&AMP;M coach Mark Johnson is hoping the  
Aggies can find their power game. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Texas A&AMP;M hit 127 home runs to break the previous  
school record of 88. Daylan Holt led the nation with 34 homers but 
went 1-for-3 in the loss to Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was one of our fears coming in,'' Johnson said. ``Good  
pitching is going to beat us. We've hit a lot of home runs against 
good pitching this year, but we have not found our stroke yet in 
Omaha.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he would start either left-hander Matt Ward (8-0,  
3.52) or first-round draft pick Chance Caple (8-5, 4.26), a righty 
who was chosen 30th overall by the St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Left-hander Jon Smith (7-0, 2.71) will throw for Fullerton. The  
Titans killed themselves with five errors in losing to Stanford, 
including three throwing errors by reliever Marco Hanlon. Still, 
Smith expressed faith in his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can't do the job, I do feel like we've got a good enough  
bullpen to take care of it,'' Smith said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
