<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Slightly Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar shot up against the yen Monday  
morning as Japan's central bank snapped up dollars to curb a rise 
in the Japanese currency. Tokyo stock prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 119.82 yen at late morning, up 1.16 yen  
from its level of 118.66 from late Friday in Tokyo, and also above 
its late New York level of 118.08 yen, also Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisuke Sakakibara, Japan's vice finance minister for  
international affairs, confirmed that the Bank of Japan had stepped 
into foreign exchange markets to stem a rising yen. Asked if the 
BOJ had intervened Monday, Sakakibara said, ``Yes. We took 
appropriate steps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Sakakibara declined to say at what level and in what  
amount the BOJ intervened, dealers said the bank may have bought as 
much as dlrs 3 billion Monday morning, and total buying could top 
dlrs 5 billion before the Asian session was through. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakakibara, known as ``Mr. Yen'' for his influence on currency  
markets, said Japan is strongly resolved to prevent an excessively 
fast strengthening of the yen to ensure economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market shouldn't underestimate our firm intention,''  
Sakakibara said. 
</P>
<P>
	A stronger yen is a threat to the exporters that power Japan's  
economy because it makes their goods more expensive overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has been rising against the dollar since the government  
announced last week that Japan's gross domestic product grew a 
robust 1.9 percent in the first quarter of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In stock trading, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average  
gained 107.00 points, or 0.62 percent, to finish the morning 
session at 17,305.55. On Friday, the average finished up 95.93 
points, or 0.56 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 10.27 points, or 0.74 percent, to 1,389.95. The 
TOPIX rose 13.07 points, or 0.96 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices were boosted by the lower yen and strong foreign  
buying following the release of much better-than-expected 
first-quarter gross domestic product data last week. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies Monday, the euro was traded at 125.83 yen,  
up from 124.70 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond dropped to 1.6650 percent from 1.7000 percent Friday, driving 
its price up to 97.72 from 97.43. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
