<HEADLINE> Robertson Reportedly Gave to Org. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson  
donated $1 million of his own money last year to help the religious 
organization through its financial crisis, Newsweek reported 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine, quoting unidentified sources, said Robertson  
recently has taken a more hands-on approach to the organization he 
formed in 1989 as it struggles with a drop in membership, faltering 
revenues and a losing battle with the Internal Revenue Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Christian Coalition is in the midst of a major  
reorganization after deciding not to contest an IRS conclusion that 
certain of its activities were too partisan for the group to enjoy 
tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
	The group, which distributes voter guides at churches around the  
country, has been identified with conservative Republican 
candidates for office. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition officials estimate the organization will owe  
the IRS between $300,000 and $400,000 in back taxes. Newsweek 
estimated that the organization has debts of $2.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate comment Sunday from the Christian  
Coalition. 
  	   	
</P>
