<DOCNO> APW19990613.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 09:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Father of Ecology May Be Honored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARABOO, Wis. (AP) -- Aldo Leopold earned his reputation as the  
father of modern ecology while working with his family to return a 
piece of abused land to its natural beauty. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-century later, within two miles of his family farm in  
southwestern Wisconsin, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service proposes 
an 8,400-acre refuge in his name. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency wants to restore wetlands that once covered much of  
the area proposed for the Aldo Leopold National Wildlife Refuge. 
</P>
<P>
	``If this is a fitting memorial to Leopold, it has to be a place  
where people can learn,'' said Nina Leopold Bradley, daughter of 
the famed naturalist. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1930s and '40s, the Leopold family trekked each weekend  
to a worn-out farm once owned by a bootlegger, planting 3,000 
native pines each year. A chicken coop became the family's living 
quarters, dubbed the Leopold ``shack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They bought the land after the bootlegger abandoned it. In one  
of Leopold's books, he wrote that ``the bootlegger, who hated this 
farm, skinned it of residual fertility, burned its farmhouse, threw 
it back into the lap of the county (with delinquent taxes to 
boot).'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the family worked, they studied the landscape and took notes,  
recorded weather patterns, bird migrations, animal tracks and 
events on the land. His best-known book, ``Sand County Almanac,'' 
was inspired by his experiences on the Baraboo farm. 
</P>
<P>
	Leopold's landmark 1933 book, ``Game Management,'' defined the  
fundamental skills for managing and restoring wildlife populations 
and led him to serve as a conservation adviser to the United 
Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the book's publication, he was appointed chairman of  
the University of Wisconsin's new Department of Game Management, a 
position he held until his death in 1948 from a heart attack while 
helping his neighbors fight a grass fire. He was 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Land for the proposed refuge, between Baraboo and Wisconsin  
Dells, would cost $12 million to acquire and would be in addition 
to about 10,000 nearby acres already protected by landowners. The 
Leopold shack has been preserved. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're talking about a much more valuable place for protecting  
wildlife,'' said Charlie Luthin, executive director of the 
Wisconsin Wetlands Association, a statewide organization dedicated 
to wetland protection and conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The refuge would be located at the convergence of Leech Creek  
and the Baraboo River. Some areas would be open to sporting 
enthusiasts since restoring the creek could increase the habitat 
for trout. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildlife officials also hope the restoration would attract more  
deer, ducks, geese, muskrats and wading birds, including herons and 
egrets. The refuge could include a visitor's center, overlook sites 
for bird watchers, hiking trails and hunting areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan faces some opposition, mostly from neighboring farmers  
reluctant to sell their land. They say the area isn't needed 
because there are other nearby refuges. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Gumz owns 1,500 acres in the core of the proposed refuge  
area, where he grows corn, mint, potatoes and soybeans. He said a 
wildlife refuge may be needed in other areas of the state, but not 
near his farm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got so many geese it's unbelievable,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Sauk County's Board of Supervisors voted in April against the  
refuge, but the Fish and Wildlife Service isn't bound by local 
government's opposition. Other county boards have not yet voted. 
</P>
<P>
	The wildlife service can't purchase more property until after an  
environmental assessment is completed this spring. So far, the 
government owns just under 10 percent of the refuge area. 
</P>
<P>
	Water once covered much of the proposed refuge area. In 1918,  
farmers began digging ditches with a steam-powered engine and 
channeled the creek. Since then, farmers have depended on the 
drainage system that crisscrosses the land to keep it from being 
overrun with water. 
</P>
<P>
	Luthin, former executive director of the Aldo Leopold  
Foundation, said he hopes farmers would come to recognize the 
potential benefits for them that come from wetland restoration. 
Restoring wetlands would help prevent the flooding of farm fields, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The creek can only hold so much water,'' Luthin said. ``The  
restored lands could work as a sponge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Lenz, project manager for the wildlife service, said  
farmers who don't want to sell their land won't be affected by 
wetland restoration nearby. The service can restore wetlands 
without flooding neighboring property that remains in private 
hands, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, who lives on the farm where her father once worked,  
said the plan would only be successful if it's a community project 
involving farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a quote from Dad,'' said Bradley, 82, a plant  
ecologist. ``'There are two things that interest me -- the 
relationship of people to each other, and the relationship of 
people to land.' 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's imposed on them, it will be a disaster,'' she said.  
``My father worked very hard to help farmers value the natural 
system as well as make a living.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
