<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Mulls Stock Float </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG has retained two U.S.  
investment banks to advise on a potential stock market float of its 
aerospace arm, The Sunday Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's objective would be to establish a market value for  
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG, paving the way for future alliances 
or mergers with other aerospace groups, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler representatives were not immediately available  
for comment on the report. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler and the investment banks, Goldman Sachs and  
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, are thought to be considering floating 
a stake of 20 percent to 30 percent in the aerospace arm, probably 
early next year, The Sunday Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new issue would value the subsidiary at about $9.6 billion  
and the shares would be listed in New York and Frankfurt, it said. 
A New York listing could make it easier for the aerospace arm to 
link with a U.S. group. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday Times said Manfred Bischoff, DaimlerChrysler  
Aerospace's chairman, is known to be holding talks with U.S. giant 
Lockheed Martin Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper said Bischoff flew to the United States this weekend,  
having canceled a press conference due to be held in conjunction 
with the Paris Air Show. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace PLC, which jilted DaimlerChrysler Aerospace  
early this year when it chose to buy General Electric Co. PLC's 
Marconi electronics business, remains eager to link with the 
aerospace company, The Sunday Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Aerospace and Spain's state-owned Construcciones  
Aeronauticas SA on Friday unveiled an agreement to merge under the 
umbrella of a new company in the DaimlerChrysler group. 
</P>
<P>
	Spain's Casa is a small but significant player in Europe's  
aerospace industry, with minority interests in both Airbus 
Industrie and the Eurofighter strike jet consortium, two key 
pan-European programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sunday Times added that the appointment of Goldman Sachs and  
Morgan Stanley as prospective global coordinators of the 
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace issue would be a blow to Deutsche Bank 
AG, which is historically Daimler's financial adviser. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
