<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tear Gas Fired As Vietnamese Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Riot police fired tear gas Sunday to quell  
clashes between Vietnamese at a refugee camp where one building was 
set on fire by a homemade bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	At least eight people were injured in the clashes. Police said  
it was not immediately known how many people were involved in the 
violence at the Pillar Point camp, which houses more than 1,000 
Vietnamese. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio Hong Kong said a gasoline bomb thrown during the fighting  
set ablaze one building in the camp. The fire was quickly 
extinguished. 
</P>
<P>
	A police spokeswoman said that police fired three chemical smoke  
grenades to halt the clashes and that the situation was under 
control. The injured were hospitalized, she said. Their condition 
was not known. 
</P>
<P>
	Police surrounded the camp after the violence and stopped people  
from entering. Pillar Point is an open camp that allows the 
Vietnamese to work outside. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately known what triggered the clash, but there  
is a long history of ethnic tensions between south and north 
Vietnamese in Hong Kong centers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1992, 24 Vietnamese were burned to death in the Shek Kong  
camp in fighting between south and north Vietnamese. The camp was 
later shut down. 
</P>
<P>
	Since communist North Vietnam defeated the U.S.-backed South in  
1975, ending the Vietnam War, nearly 223,000 Vietnamese have passed 
through Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the Hong Kong government abolished its 23-year-old  
policy of offering temporary asylum to the Vietnamese and shut down 
government-run detention centers for them. 
</P>
<P>
	Vietnamese who arrive illegally now are housed in detention  
centers run by charitable organization until arrangements can be 
made to send them back. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong still harbors more than 2,000 Vietnamese asylum  
seekers. About 1,500 have been granted refugee status and are 
awaiting resettlement overseas. The rest are waiting to be deported 
back home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
